column6: Magnum Men's Viper Pro 8 SZ Waterproof Duty Boot
column13: Doesn't do the Magnum boot name justice.
column14:
A long time wearer of Magnums. In my rough day-to-day wear, I found them to last about a year, give or take a few months. That always seemed fair for me since I'd buy them two at a time at some place that offered buy one get one half off. They took well to a buff and always looked professional.

Eventually, I bought 6 pairs of the Viper II line, not waterproof. Rub in some mink oil, spray with KIWI, and re-oil/spray every month or two, and I'm good. They took SEVERE abuse, including lots of rain, puddles, mud, soft earth, shallow swamps and accidental dunks when misjudging said water sources, and I never had a single problem.

I decided to finally upgrade and try these out after I ran through all my old Vipers. These are supposed to be WATERPROOF, and I know what that entails with these: light rain and a puddle or two are a-okay, but anything heavy or deeper than your ankle and you're severely pushing it and should've donned rubbers.

First impressions were good. They looked like a good leather and a Gore-Tex type weave. The tab to help pull the boot on is leather instead of fabric, but it's too low and short to be of real help. Maybe making it a loop would've been better. Finally, the leather looked more matte than my previous boots, but I like it. It's easier to maintain a professional look than shiny leather.

I broke them in the usual way: a day of wearing them around the house chasing my son. I immediately noticed they were more narrow than my previous Vipers in wide (EE), but I figured I'd let them stretch naturally instead of a boot stretcher. I haven't dealt with waterproof inner linings, so I didn't want to take a chance.

I had one assignment in light rain. They did their job ‚Äì my feet stayed dry and I finished out the day; HOWEVER, the next day the "leather" was rubbing off of the toe!

The leather doesn't feel right anymore. It feels like it soaked up a lot of water. The lining kept medry, but the leather seems easily damaged. After being dry enough on the surface and needing to wear them again, I went to take my buff sponge to it quickly and the leather flaked and crumbled off the toe. I also obviously see some of the glue used to finish the sole.

These disappoint me. One star for not being a catastrophic failure and one star for keeping my feet dry... one day.

I'm returning these and do not recommend them.

column6: DC Mens Cole Lite 3 S Shoes
column14: I have been skating with the Cole Lite 3s for a week and a half now, all street skating. Pulling them out of the box, their light weight is readily apparent. When skating, they don't feel like they're weighing you down at all. The soles allow for good grip and feel of the board, but not so much so that the vibrations are issue. They are good for just cruising as well since the shoes are very comfortable. I cannot speak on arch support as I have very flat feet. The laces are a bit further back from the toe end of the shoe which lends to lack of wear on the laces for flip tricks. For overall durability, The shoe is still holding up just fine, but I think the toe ends will wear through relatively quickly as the harder suede lining around the edge is already starting to fade from repeated flip tricks. I think if this had a harder toe cap to enhance its durability, it may be the perfect skate shoe.

column13: Merrell, what has become of you?
column14: I have been a Merrell customer for many years. Their sneakers, boots and sandals have always fit well and have been very comfortable. However, these are the second pair of Merrell sandals I am returning this year. The fit of this sandal seems to be a half size larger and wider but the worst of it is that these are not the Merrell quality I am used to. The straps are leather but are lined with a cheap nylon and the foot bed is made of a hard, stiff plastic which I'm sure will be uncomfortable and make my feet hot, not at all like the flexible, absorbent material they have used in the past.  I returned the previous pair also because of inferior quality, but I wanted to give them another chance. I am very disappointed that I can no longer buy Merrells with confidence. They have lost a loyal customer.

column6: MLC Eyewear Vintage Classic Fashion Aviator Sunglasses Tri-Layer UV400 Unisex
column14: These vintage aviator sunglasses came as a surprise to me. When I ordered them, I did not pay attention to the color of the lenses that I ordered. When I received them in the mail, I was shocked at the rich red color of the lenses. When I tried them on, they fit well, and I liked them just fine, but I realized that I knew someone who could put them to much better use. My mother. My mother was born with Achromatopsia, which is a hereditary visual disorder, characterized by decreased vision, light sensitivity, and the absence of color vision. It turns out, that the only color lenses that are comfortable for her to wear out in the sun, (we live in the Florida sun at that), is RED. While she owns a pair of red sunglasses, her lenses are small, and the boxy plastic frames annoy her. I immediately ran in to give these to her, and she was so happy she almost cried. These sunglasses covered her field of vision wonderfully, and the red color is so rich that she can comfortably walk outside to watch her children play, or even to check the mail. I LOVE these glasses. They answered a prayer.

column14:
Loved these shoes right out of the box! I received them at work and after trying them on real quick, I didn't want to go back to my other shoes. I ended up buying the same pair twice because the price dropped significantly while I was waiting for them to arrive and just figured I would return the first, more expensive pair and keep the second, cheaper pair...but when I showed my mom and she tried them on, she asked if she could keep them and just write me a check haha. (She wore them that whole day and has worn them several times since and loves them too).

I should note that yesterday, I wore them when I went for a walk in the park with a friend, and after about a mile, the front strap did start to rub a blister on my pinky toe...but I've also worn them to Disneyland for several hours and had no pain or issues that day..so it could have been a fluke, or the heat or just the faster more "exercise" pace of the walking. Regardless I'm very happy with them and have already bought another style of fitflops! I'm a runner and am realizing that it's time to start taking better care of my body and I love that I've found a sandal that helps with that.

I'm going to Disneyworld next month and plan to wear these sandals quite a bit!

column14: I have to say, I'm not a fan of these kind of shoes ( loafers/boat shoes ), I don't like how they look, they are not my style, so I don't ever buy anything like this. Plus, because of my high arches, I'm weary of anything flat flat. It makes my whole body, not just my legs, tired and sore in no time.  But, I read so many reviews online praising these to be so unbelievable comfy, and as I was looking for some kind of a summer shoe that is not open, and it's comfortable enough for running around the city all day if necessary... I took my chances with these. And, oh my! They truly are so unbelievably comfy! Gotta love 'em, even though I still don't quite like how they look ( but, that's just me and my personal preferences ). But, I'll forgive them their looks, I'll forgive them anything just because of that amazing comfort they provide.  They do run quite wide. I got them in my true size, and they fit perfectly... But, being so wide, my feet/heels slip out sometimes as I walk. I tried half size smaller the other day in store, but that was painfully tight length wise ( and especially front wise )... But, they were still so wide. Even though the front of the shoes was painfully tight, these, too, were about to let my heels slip out as I was walking around. I guess it is just the model of this shoe, and one should take it into consideration. They are true to size, but run too wide. I can deal with it. But, I'm still looking for some kind of "fix" for this "situation", so if anybody has any idea, please let me know.   These shoes are so comfortable, they even provide support for my high arches. I can run around the city all day wearing these without a problem. No blisters, no pain, no tired feet, no pain in legs and lower back.... I don't even think about wearing anything else when I know I'm gonna have a lot of running around in front of me... So, they are keepers. Even with that one "lil" "negative" detail. :) ( And, that is why 4 stars )Other than that, I absolutely love them. Even their look is starting to grow on me. :) Ummm.... I even got another pair of these, in different color. :)

column6: 3 Pair of Classic Unisex Bifocal Sunglasses - Outdoor Reading Sunglasses
column14:
My father is hands down the roughest person with glasses of all time. He never wore them as a child, but cancer left him with poorer vision and now he needs readers. The man is a sunglass lover; he will wear them on the cloudiest days. Now, he likes his sunglasses to have a bifocal reader portion to them. We used to purchase them in store, but they were so expensive.
So happy we found these guys! He loves the colors and they work exceptionally well for their intended purpose.
At first, the seller sent us the wrong item but worked quickly to resolve the issue. Thanks, seller!
Overall, happy with the purchase and based on my dad's track records with glasses, we will be back for more in the future!

column13: The best shoes I have ever owned!!
column14: I bought these about 8 months ago and wanted to see how long they lasted and wearability.  The first thing I noticed is that they are incredibly light and comfortable because of the memory foam lining.  I am a HS Chemistry teacher on my feet all day at least 10 hours and after 65 years of wearing shoes these are the MOST COMFORTABLE I have ever owned.  Good looks????? at my age I really do not care.  They have survived toxic spills and deep rain puddles and clean and restore within a short time.  They adapt to all surfaces including gravel and have never  accused them of being slippery.  i quit wearing dress shoes and wear these exclusively.  I can't wait until the Go Walk 4's come out!!

column14:
These shoes hold up really well. I bought them to wear on an archaeological excavation in the desert and they are still in great shape five weeks later. A lot of other people had the issue of their soles melting off (and this on $80 shoes), but mine held together great. I would recommend buying the largest size you typically buy, as the toes are a little narrow. And if you plan to spend more than a couple hours in them at a time I would also get insoles as they have little so far as arch support when you are on you feet for eight hours at a time. Other than that, they are super comfortable and are worth the money.

Even after the dig, I am still wearing them to work!

column13: A near perfect rating for these awesome shoes!
column14:
I was very pleased with my my purchase of Twisted kix black plaid shoes. I purchased a size 6 which typically I wear a size 5.5, the size 6 was a near perfect fit and a 5.5 would have most likely have been too slender for my foot as the size 6 is perfectly snug fit as per width, if I had gone a size smaller I don't think I'd be as happy with the product, this would be the only advisory I'd post regarding this brand.
Otherwise the shoes are surprisingly sturdy in build as per their price bracket. No inconsistencies in the shoe itself. No discomfort, in fact these are possible one of the most comfortable shoes I've worn straight out of the box! I can only imagine the comfort increases with time as the shoe shapes to accomodate your feet. The fabric clearly of quality, the rubber portion of the shoes are not as up to par on quality as I can see these most likely won't get years of usage, but at the same time I feel confident they will last me a full 12 months at least. The color and design is fabulously adorable! I've placed an order for 2 more pairs in various colors I love them that much! All in all the price was more than right and I am beyond happy with my choice in product!

column6: Easy Spirit Watersedge Mary Jane Shoes
column14: This is a classic Easy Spirit style that has had various names.  Watersedge has the same ES stability, comfort and quality of the others with an nice improvement.  The upper shoe has less mesh for more durability.  My little and big toe would eventually tear a hole through the mesh of the older versions.  I wear Watersedge all day and love it for travel.  It's a more stylish alternative to a lace up walking shoe.  I gave it 4 stars because one change is not a particularly welcome one: the strap is now made of elastic, not leather.  I hope the elastic will last and not stretch out.  As a new shoe, I find the elastic does not give the stability I am used to. If ES would go back to a solid strap, this one would be perfect.

column13: Perfect boot for city to mild-moderate on a whim trails
column14: I bought these boots right before moving to New Zealand. I have to say they are the best boots I've had. Out of the box I was able to walk around all day without the need for breaking them in. I had no blisters at the end of the day. It was pouring rain at times and I was on a mix of city streets and muddy trails (mild-moderate hike) and my feet stayed bone dry. I have now worn them daily for a week and feel equally as happy with them. The elastic like material on the ankle makes them easy to get on. They have a great fashionable look to them as well and go with pants or skirts/dresses. I will note that there I don't think there is much ankle support, which is fine for me as I don't tend to have ankle issues, but for others that may wander up a trail in these may want to keep that in mind. I don't think they are meant for hiking, but I have found them great for my on a whim trails discovered here and there.

column6: Vibram FiveFingers Women's TrekSport Cross-Trainer Shoes,Light Grey,39 M EU
column14:
First, let me say that by "fits as expected" I mean that I ordered a size larger than I would normally based on the Vibram site's size calculator and some reviews, so fits as expected by "them". I did not get to try on the size smaller, but the ones I have seem to fit well, possibly a wee tad large, but if so, it is not a problem. As I walk, my toes slide to the ends, yet they don't feel loose at the heels. I couldn't find a convenient local store to try them on -- our EMS is too small. Second, this is my second pair of toe shoes, but my first Vibrams. My first were Fila Skeletoes, which I liked quite well and lasted about 4-5 years. I would have gotten another pair of Filas, but they look different and I found these for the same price in a color I liked better.

This model seemed to be the closest I could find to the Skeletoes I loved in terms of being good for both walking/hiking/running and water sports. They have a little more aggressive tread, which will probably come in handy, yet they feel just as barefoot as my Filas. The top being mesh makes them less hot and stinky, and there's an antimicrobial something-or-other involved that may help that, too. I have worn them twice without feeling the need to wash them yet. I assume they'll dry faster, too. My only concern with the mesh is that it might get caught on a stick and rip easily. These seal around my foot better and are higher in the back, which should help keep debris and sand from sneaking in -- as much fun as it sounds. The only thing I like better about my old Filas is that the inside of these feels rougher. I'm wondering if they will give me callouses over time if I wear them a lot. I hope they hold up as well over time as my Filas did ... and that Fila goes back to making them (seem to no longer be making them).

Fyi, I use these mostly for trail walking for trips of an hour or so, occasional trail or road running and very occasional swimming. I findthey are very handy to keep in the car so I can always be prepared for any adventure in three seasons, especially on road trips. The barefoot feel is kind of neat, though not good on dirt roads with coarse gravel/stones -- too painful over time. And on walks in the woods, you'll look down on occasion and find that your toes are sprouting ferns. : ) You do occasionally wind up having to pick out a painful stick or small rock from the toes, and do be careful of stubbing your toes. It can be an exercise in mindfulness when walking or running in woods -- you need to pay attention to where you are putting your feet, but I find that while I'm busy trying not to break a toe, the miles are rolling under me. : )

Oh -- these came with an odd little storage (?) bag. I guess it would be good for packing them in a suitcase, but so would a ziplock . I have no idea why there's a hole in the middle -- to suspend it on a pole? Seems unnecessary -- I'd rather have them be a little cheaper and skip the silly bag.

Brought these at the suggestion of my trainer and absolutely love them. I have a solid connection with the floor and can really focus on my placement and movement. Arch support seems good so far. Loved the "Find the Right Size" tool on the Amazon page. I put in model and size of my current shoe to find out what size I should order for the Nano. I wear a 10.5 in the DMX, but an 11 in the Nano. column6: Skechers USA Men's Diameter Memory Foam Casual Slip On
column13: I took a chance and lost...
column14:
I've owned this exact style of Sketcher and similar for many years(have you ever had shoes without shoe strings? ask Kanye West...).
Keep in mind while you read this that every pair of Sketchers without laces prior to this have been nothing short of amazing.

I got these on a lightening deal for about $20 off so I really wanted them to work out.

The first pair I received sounded like you were walking on glue strips.
- Every step sounded like you were peeling your shoes off a sticky floor covered in half dried soda.
- They fit perfect with no issues in the soles(see second pair).

The second pair I received did not have the glue strip sound when walking(so first pair was an anomaly).
- The first pair must have been a defect.
- Unfortunately the sole was not put in properly on the second pair leaving a bump in the rear of the heel.
- The poor glue job on the insole made it feel like you were walking on a rock all the time. Not fun.

The third pair never came unfortunately.
- I requested third pair through the return process which was accepted, but the seller canceled the order and refunded the money.
- I really wanted this style of Sketchers, and they are normally $70 or so on here so I wasn't happy the seller didn't send the third pair.
- Does the seller think I'm making this stuff up? The issues with the shoes I got were easy to confirm.

I bought a different style of sketchers very close to this style in black(same time I bought these with the deal), and they were perfect as expected.
I have this same exact pair that is over 3 years old that are still wearable(no major cracks in the leather, and look good).
Note that I treat all my Sketchers with leather protection to make them last longer(it makes a difference, spend the 10 bucks to protect them).

Bottom line:
I would buy these Sketchers again for $50/60 just to see if they are all defective(took years for my old ones to wear, still kicking).
Fortunately I have Amazon Prime with no hassle returns.ok years for my old ones to wear, still kicking).
Fortunately I have Amazon Prime with no hassle returns.

column6: Baggallini Everywhere Lightweight Crossbody Bag - Multi-Pocketed, Spacious Water-Resistant Travel Purse with RFID Wristlet
column14: Very handy. Love the wipe-clean finish, the paprika color very true to photos. Will buy another when (if?) this one wears out. Some women have multiple handbags, but I'm not one of them. I get one bag that I love and use it until it wears out. This is that kind of bag. Plus it comes in great colors. My favorite thing is that it has a cell phone pouch on the front, so I never have to search for my phone, and there is a zipper pouch next to it, where I keep my keys, so they're always handy. No perfect place for pens, but I use one of the end zipper pouches. There are two pen loops inside the main section at the top, but they're a bit awkward. Holds everything that I want to carry with me and then some. It could hold a lot more, but then it'd be too heavy. But when I have kids with me or I'm traveling, I can really load it up; though it holds it's shape when sparsely filled. Some bags look odd when nearly empty, which mine never seems to be. Only thing I don't like is the zipper on the bottom of the bag opens up a pocket that has a top zipper. So, if somehow it gets pulled open when you're not expecting it to be, like if the zipper tab got snagged on something or a kid yanked it, all the stuff in that pocket would just spill out. I've never had that happen, but the first time I unzipped that, expecting to find another compartment, I was surprised to see my stuff falling through. Maybe it's to make cleaning out the purse easier. I don't know, but it's not a big deal for me, and I love this bag.

column13: I usually love Clarks shoes and have never had a problem with ...
column14:
I usually love Clarks shoes and have never had a problem with the fit before. However these shoes do NOT fit true to size at all, and there is very little cushioning. I am a true 7, and these shoes squeeze my foot and are extremely uncomfortable especially in the toe area and ball of the foot. The toe area is super narrow and small, it rubs against the little toe and pinches your feet. Also the back of the boot is somehow loose and seems like it doesn't completely fit your heel. Its weird.

The heel height is perfect, not too high, and it seemed like these would be great, but they're not.

If you absolutely must buy these shoes, I would recommend buying 1/2 size up, buying a "wide" fit, and wearing them at home for an hour to make sure that you feel comfortable in them. Because they really are not comfortable. *tear*

column14: I've been wearing them nonstop since they arrived. I like them.  I just ordered a second pair in another color.  Too bad Patagonia is no longer making shoes.  The long laces thing‚Ä¶ come on people, use some scissors, cut the nylon lace to your spec, then use a match to light the new cut and to keep them from fraying.  Longish is better than shortish.  Cut to fit.  Recommend these for sure.

column6: Birkenstock Womens Gizeh EVA Sandals
column14: I've worn many Birkenstocks styles over the years, both clogs and sandals, but this is my first experience with the Gizeh. I was a bit timid about ordering from a vendor based outside the US (these are shipped from Germany), but the experience was smooth and the shoes arrived in about a week. I achieved an excellent fit by ordering my "regular" Birkenstock size. I'm a bit mixed about this new take on the Birkenstock. If (like me), you're used to the arch support you get from the traditional Birkenstock latex+cork footbed, you won't find that same support in the EVA footbed here. It's simply a different material and has an entirely different feel than the latex+cork. However, I still think these are comfortable sandals/flips and I'm happy with them. Th huge advantage they provide over the traditional Birkenstocks is that they can GET WET! That means I can wear them to the beach and pool (or even get caught in the rain), which is exactly what I was looking for. I'm a bit concerned about how the sole will wear (i.e. wear out) over time, as they don't seem very durable, but I don't have much experience with this material, so hopefully I will be happily surprised!

column6: SKORA Men's Phase-X Running Shoe
column13: Great Barefoot feel, minor caveat on the upper.
column14:
TAKE OUT THE INSOLE, it becomes a different shoe!

Pro: (1) Fits True to size (2) NO overlay issues (3) Super flexibility adapts to your foot (4) Great barefoot feel
Con: Upper mesh does not breathe as well as other brands --not for sweaty feet in the summer.

I bought these shoes online, sight unseen. Having run in NB's and Merrells in the past couple of years, I felt fairly confident about my choice.
No disappointment-- right out of the box, they first felt bulky and tight -- until I pulled out the insole (looked and felt about a 2mm difference) which made a nice roomy improvement.
I appreciated the rounded heel for running, since it was automatic feedback on whether or not I was properly landing on my midfoot, or hitting my heel too hard. Online, they looked a bit narrow, but they held my Fred-Flintstone feet perfectly. Also, even though these were an ounce or two heavier than my Merrell's, I definitely did not feel it as I ran at my usual pace with no extra effort.

The ONLY thing I could somewhat complain about is the closed-mesh material of the upper -- if you're the sweaty-foot type -- or in my case, sweaty-everywhere type.... these shoes don't feel like they breathe all that well. (Perhaps the Finns, understandably, are not as concerned with sweating as we Californians) This could be a concern if you're paranoid about blistering, or live in a humid area. This is the only reason I took off a star, otherwise the shoe is pretty close to perfect.
Two Non-complaints : (1) I posted that there is no arch support, but being a barefoot-type shoe, there really shouldn't be. (2) Not so good as a casual walking shoe, because there is a chance that after several minutes, it will clobber your heels if you're not careful (I heel-strike when I walk). But all racing flats seem to be that way.

BOTTOM LINE: If you are already running with short, quick, light steps, give these yummy slippers a try.

column6: Red Wing Heritage Iron Ranger 6-Inch Boot
column14: These are my second pair of Iron Rangers , so there were no surprises regarding the fit or quality.  As a higher priced boot, I can assure you the quality really is second to none.  If loved and cared for, they will last you a lifetime I suspect.  Regarding the fit, I was fortunate enough to have an actual Red Wing dealer here in MN to assist me on my first pair.  So, after a measurement and fitting, I can confidently say that they generally run a full size large in length.  The width I would say tends to be true to size; thus my purchase of the wide size.  As a matter of comparison, I would typically purchase an 11 1/2 in a Frye boot to accommodate my wide foot and for length sake (Frye rarely makes a wide sized shoe...).  If you're having doubts, just google this boot and you'll see a multitude of blogs and pics all in adoration of these American classics.  As jaded as I am at times, even I have to jump on the band wagon on these...

If you are using it for travel, just remember that it's not theft proof (it's not advertised to be so that shouldn't come as a shock). column6: Timberland PRO Mens Helix 6\ Waterproof Safety Toe"
column13: All around great but the manufacturing quality seems to have dipped
column14:
I bought these to replace my old pair of Helix's so I knew mostly what I was in for. I have pretty wide feet so it took about three days for the shoe to give in to the fact that my pinky toe wasn't going anywhere, it was the same on my first pair and just like then after a week these things are SO comfortable to put on.

My old pair had really chopped up toes by the time I was done with them, this pair has already taken some hits so I went ahead and ordered an epoxy to shield up the toe. This is a recommendation more than a knock on the boot - when you have a safety toe the leather is going to get a beating.

Personally I don't like the feel of the laces it comes with so I swap them out for some longer 63" paracord laces so I can tie the boots in my own special way, but that's just me. What is pretty cool is there's sort of a cinch on the eyelet right at your ankle which locks in the laces after you pull them tight, keeping them snug while you tie them up.

The anti fatigue feature is great at first but definitely falls off over the life of the boot, I think I had my old pair for about two years and at the end I was slipping some new soles in to keep my legs comfortable. I don't count this against the boots, wear and tear is absolutely expected and 2 years is a good lifespan to me. As for the ladder hooking design in the treads, ehhh. Kind of a gimmick to me. Admittedly I don't spend a ton of time on extension ladders but really I've never thought to myself, "I wish someone made a boot that made ladders easier to stand on." Also if anything having the middle of your foot bear the weight, as opposed to the toe or heel, is kinda uncomfortable after a short amount of time.

What my real gripe is, and why this is a 4 star review, is that out of the box there was some separation between the treads and the leather on either side of both boots. Not cool. This was NOT present on my old pair until the end of their life so I thought nothing of it then. I bought some Shoe Goo to patch it up but seriously Timberland tighten up.life so I thought nothing of it then. I bought some Shoe Goo to patch it up but seriously Timberland tighten up.

column6: Saucony Men's Stabil CS3 Running Shoe
column14: I have been wearing Brooks Beast Shoes for several years when refereeing soccer games on artificial turf during the high school season (the winter, here in California) and I loved the stability, support and cushioning, but wasn't so fond of the price.  I thought I'd give the Saucony Stabil a try -- seeing that they were also available in a wide width and promised much of the same type of support and stability for my flat, over-pronating feet.  I just wore them last weekend for working a boys showcase tournament -- two U15 games and the U16 and U19 finals and I found my feet were rather sore just behind the toes.  I removed the innersoles and discovered that they are incredibly cheap and flimsy compared to those that come with the Brooks Beast (which have innersoles providing gel comfort from toe to heel).  I have replaced the Saucony innersoles with some from an old pair of Brooks, I can already tell that they are much more comfortable.  So, basically if you buy these, you may want to factor in the cost of a decent pair of orthotics in with the cost!

column6: BG® Women Smooth PU Leather Shoulder Handbags
column13: Beautiful purse that's very versatile and looks amazing!
column14:
[[VIDEOID:fed116a0c24446b59d20596f9e01eb27]]I'm not sure I can adequately describe how much I love this purse. BG has always impressed me with the quality of their bags, and this one is no exception...but seriously, this bag is amazing! I got it in the dark green, and it just looks absolutely stunning with the brown and gold accents. I'm not always a huge fan of straps on a purse, and prefer to use the shoulder strap, so I love the fact that you can not only adjust these straps, but you can remove them too!

The quality is outstanding. I love the silky material used inside the purse and it looks amazing. The design of this purse is pretty fantastic. It has one zipper pocket on the front, but the inside has THREE different compartments, which I love! I also love the fact that you can zipper the entire purse shut. Sometimes my purse is such a hot mess that I'm embarrassed for anyone to see inside it, and this is perfect because I can just zipper it closed and no one has to realize what a mess I am. I also like it as a safety feature. When I'm out at the store I prefer to keep my purse zippered shut. I have a fear of people just reaching into my bag and grabbing my wallet and this isn't a concern when it's zippered shut.

I can not say enough good things about this purse and the brand. The purse came in a dust cover, which I love because it keeps my purse in excellent condition when I switch out to a different purse. The purse also comes with a scented satchel that you can leave in or take out!

I received this product for free in exchange for my honest, unbiased review.

column13: New Saratoga runs larger than the Older, Discontinued Version
column14:
Bought the original version of these from G------- recently in the light grey color and loved them, so I bought these pink Saratogas in the same size (7). Very pretty color. They are comfy, but after wearing them around the house awhile, I noticed a few differences. 1. This shoe is about a half size longer than the original (more shoe behind my heel) 2. The band around the foot is slightly larger (the band only barely touches my foot at the distal edge, and gaps at the proximal edge), 3. Perhaps because the toe of the shoe is too large my foot slides forward and my toe occasionally touches the toe of the shoe (the deal breaker), and 4. The sole of the original shoe appears to be a cushy/firm leather material, but he sole of this pink shoe is a cushy/firm foam material, softer and less arch support than the original.
These will be going back. Haven't yet decided if I will try a smaller size. If my toe hadn't touched the end of the shoe I probably would have kept them.

column6: Sperry Top-Sider Women's Bahama Washed Fashion Sneaker
column14:
These Top-Siders fit me great! Normally, Sperry's are a bit wide for me (I have narrow heels) and I have to adjust the laces around the back to keep them on. Usually on the Sperry Bahama Top-Sider I also put an insole with arch support in.

These fit me right out of the box, a little loose, but still comfortable. They are wide enough in the toe box (i.e., not narrow) but the heel fits great. There isn't great arch support, but a slight arch.

The laces could be adjusted for slightly narrower or for wider feet. You could put low socks on if you wanted, but I find they are really comfortable to just slide into.

They are really cute and totally comfortable. I now have them in pink, gray, navy and white.

column6: Wild Diva Womens Pointy Toe Ankle T-Strap Gold Stud Stiletto Heel Pump Sandal
column14:
These shoes are beautiful. That's the ONLY reason I'm not returning them.* Well, that plus I don't want to pay return postage on a pair of inexpensive shoes.
Let me run down a Pro and Con list for these shoes; you can decide on your own if they're worth it to you. My stats: I'm kinda old to be wearing ridiculous shoes like this, but I am a daily heel wearer of 3" - 4". Not a novice. I have size 7 feet; they're a little wide but not so much that I need a special shoe width usually.
PROS: Beautiful. Really, these are very, very colorful and fun to look at.
For a cheap knock-off, the quality is fairly good. The studs are evenly placed, the stitching is even, and there's minimal glue marks. The buckle stays in place.
They're made out of cloth. Not that awful faux suede, nor a too-shiny satin. The fabric looks like a cotton sateen but is most likely a poly.
I have to say it again - the shoes are gorgeous.
CONS: Hideously uncomfortable. I'm used to a high heel, but these shoes were not designed well in terms of angle and balance. They're meant to be sitting-in-a-restaurant shoes, not dancing-at-the-club shoes. Or really, they're posing-for-your-blog shoes. I work at an office with minimal walking (like, to the copier and back) and I had to take them off mid morning and put on my spare flats.
Cheap materials; these shoes should have one more buckle closure in order to optimize the fit and comfort. They only have one, so you have to do a weird foot and ankle contortion to get your foot in the shoe. If you have thicker ankles, you may be out of luck even if the shoes technically fit.

So, if you're desperate to find a Rockstud 1970's dupe to photograph for your blog or your Insta, I guess this is your pair. If you want a shoe to actually wear and walk in, keep looking. I don't mind cheap shoes, I've worn plenty a Payless. But these are just beautiful torture devices.
*I bought one of those wall-mounted shelf/box things. These shoes are now a lovely conceptual art piece in my office. Everyone admires how beautiful they are, so I guess I got my money's worth after all.ted shelf/box things. These shoes are now a lovely conceptual art piece in my office. Everyone admires how beautiful they are, so I guess I got my money's worth after all.

column6: Reebok Men's RealFlex Scream 4.0 Running Shoe
column13: they offer good support, and one you get used to the ...
column14:
My shoe use consists of running, usually about 15 minutes of sprints and 45 minutes of jogging on a track 5 days a week and running trails once a week. I wasn't a huge fan of Reebok shoes I've tried in the past, but I've been pleasantly surprised with this pair; they offer good support, and one you get used to the way the shoe feels, are quite comfortable.

Pros:
Good durability despite soft material on the soles and a mesh upper.
Comfortable once you get used to the unique feelings.
Cushions the impact of running; the bottoms of my feet seem to have less muscle soreness in these shoes than most others.
Wide Enough. I have fairly wide and tall feet and these fit fine in my normal size. If you have muscular feet, you might notice touching on the side like I did at first, but that goes away rather quickly.

Cons:
A bit long. Not so much that it gets in the way, but you can feel it.
Stuff gets stuck in these shoes. If you run trails, a lot of stuff.
Arch support could be better, but it's there. I'd sat it's better than your average running shoe, but not as good as say a tennis shoe.

Overall:
I'd recommend this shoe if you can get it for the right price. I wouldn't pay $60+, but for the sale price of $28 that I got it for it's an excellent shoe.

column13: Nice separate compartments, No credit card slots
column14:
I really love that this wristlet has two completely separate compartments so that I can place my iphone in its own compartment. Its a great way to protect your phone from getting scratched by other items in your bag. As the compartments are separated by two layers of the faux leather instead of just fabric, it provides MUCH better protection than most bags. The color is great but it is a little darker than what is pictured. More like a royal blue. I also really like the heart pattern.

Now for the Negatives. First of all, there are no credit card slots or small zippered pockets for cash. I think this is a major oversight and really limits the usefulness of this wristlet. Second, is the zipper buttons clang together when you walk and make a tinging, bell like sound. Its a little annoying and its made worse by if you have a tendency to swing your arms or talk with your hands. Finally, I'm not really sure what the symbols on the zippers mean...lol

column6: Flojos Men's Cole Ii Flip Flop
column14: The title is no joke.  I currently have several different pairs of sandals: ripcurls, oneille, reef!!  Each one of the "higher end" sandals I own, have some sort of defect with them.  The ripcurls tear where your feet rub over a short period of time.  My oneill pair has symbols pop off easy.  The reefs even have issues, the strap portion that goes over your foot will break down and the design will crack & fade.  These flojos are the best pair of sandals I have.  They don't breakdown where your foot rubs on them, the straps are well made and won't break easy like some others I've owned.  These are literally the only pair of sandals I can wear all day walking in, soft base and durability construction.  The "boutique" brands I own are not nearly as comfortable.  The only pair of the 3 other brands I own would be the reefs in terms of comfort & walkability.

column14:
I bought these shoes earlier in the summer before a white-water rafting trip. These were perfect. They performed perfectly in and out of the water and the protected my wife's feet just fine. I was worried that they would be an uncomfortable mess when we walked around on the sandy banks with wet shoes, but they were just fine. The sand didn't gunk up inside them at all.

The fit and adjustment for these shoes was very convenient and comfortable. My wife was really surprised how comfortable the foot-bed was. These were actually really comfortable to walk around in, even when we weren't on the river.

These also had better treads that the sandals that I bought for myself and others in my family. Three of us had a lot of trouble with the slippery souls on our water sandals, but my wife did just fine (yay!).

column6: Zarapack Women's Pu Leather Hologram Clutch Handbag Chain Shoulder Bag
column14:
I love this purse! I own a considerable amount of holographic silver leather items, and by far this one is the most vibrant. It's extremely linear and smooth, not to mention very large. I was afraid of getting a thin, small clutch-- it's more like a short messenger bag. Has good pockets and wrist strap too.
The chain was a little hard to find... it's in the middle pocket in a tiny bag. The chain is also a little short for me (5'5") as I wanted it to function as a crossbody. However, it's not made to be one, so no complaint there. I simply attached a second chain to add length. Another problem that should be expected is, if you put too much into the purse, it won't close and the chain will put a lot of stress on your shoulder. The bigger and softer the strap, the easier it is to distribute weight. Since the chain is thin and hard, it should only be expected to hurt using too much weight. I might try and find a thicker crossbody strap. But for most people, the strap should be fine! On me, using it like a normal purse, the bag reaches my hips. Since my hips are also considerable, this would make pushing past people in halls difficult. So again, for my own personal needs, I might exchange straps. Good buy, though! I love it!

column6: Birkenstock Women's Arizona  Birko-Flo Sandals
column14:
Update: More problems - the faux leather upper is now tearing and the sandals are basically unuseable. It's only been a year and three months since purchase. When I bought Birkenstocks back in the early 90s, I wore them for almost a decade before the leather failed. I'm very disappointed in this purchase.

Update - Longevity test fails.

After only three months, the cork is cracking and falling apart on the heel of the left sandal, and the glue is giving way that holds the upper to the cork/side.

These are not the Birks I remember. I spent a lot of money for a pair of sandals that I could have got at the dollar store.
------------------------------------------
I chose the Birko-Flor due primarily to price; they are significantly less expensive than the leather version. I was skeptical, but after wearing them for a couple of weeks (and I mean everyday, all day), I've come to really appreciate them. They have everything the leather version offers - the quality, the comfort and fit, etc. - but at a more wallet friendly price.

We'll see about the longevity. My previous pair (essentially the leather version of what I have now) lasted almost a decade before I had to toss them. I'm curious as to whether these will provide the same long wear...

So far, so good.

I do like these glasses but there is a "but..." The lenses are clear and good for me for reading. They do look good. And they come with a handy little carry bag.

Most important for me was the good fit with a 14mm bridge. My nose is quite narrow and somewhat deep set so most average size (or no size listed) readers just skip down my nose or fall off. So happy these stay on.

The "but"... the wires that the nose pads fit to seem very soft, my impression while adjusting width between pads. So I've been very careful with then, though I am typically pretty rough on readers.

Bottom line - if readers tend to slip off your nose, try these. Just don't sit on them (note to self).

column6: Vibram Women's Alitza Loop Fitness Yoga Shoe
column13: The Alitza Loop did not fit like regular Alitza.  The pinky toe housing was too small.
column14:
I wear a size 8 - 8.5 women's shoe.

These were my third pair of Fivefingers but unfortunately they didn't fit. I ordered the same size as my two prior pairs, that is size 39, and the Alitza Loop fit great EXCEPT for the pinky toe. The pinky toe housing was too short and too narrow. All other toes fit normally, but I couldn't even straighten out my pinky toe in the tiny space allotted for it. Please note, I have slender feet and short toes and a very small pinky toe so this really didn't make any sense.

I was committed to owning these so I exchanged the 39's for 40's and same problem. With the 40's the regular toes were too long and pinky toe space was still too small to straighten out my small pinky toe.

Normal Alitza fit me perfectly in size 39, but Alitza Loop in 39 and 40 - I could barely get my pinky toe in much less move efficiently in these. Sadly, they had to go back. :,(

column6: Le Chameau Footwear Women's Vierzon Rain Boot
column14:
I ordered a size 10. I haven't worn them out walking but if they don't wear comfortably all day I'll be very surprised and disappointed. The fit is narrower than many boots but perfect for me. I have a high arch so I got orthotic inserts but had to have the shoe man thin it out from the ball to the toe. I don't have skinny calves but there was just enough room, allowing for socks and (sometimes) pants. Check le chameau website for calf measurement if that's a concern. By way of comparison: they replace a pair of Lacrosse boots which of course I could only get in men's but they run narrow as men's boots go. I still had to wear extremely thick socks as my feet were swimming in them (especially after they started leaking :).

They'll earn five stars if they hold up.

column13: Love Frye but beware on these
column14: I have several pairs of Frye boots both in tall and short and they have all fit true to size so I ordered these in my size.  These boots are tall and do not have a zipper therefore you have to shimmy your foot down the shaft of the boot to get it on.... IF you can.  I could not in my size and back they went to Amazon.  I ordered a 1/2 size up and I was able to SQUEEZE my feet into them, then the heel area was a little loose and slipped a bit.  I know you can wear thicker socks but I probably  would not be able to get my feet through the boot shaft. I wore them only a couple of hours before they became unbearable. They are very stiff and there is no arch support in this style.  I was surprised that they were marked "Made In Mexico".  I always thought that Frye was made in America.  I love the look of the boot and plan to take them to a shoe shop to get them stretched widthwise. I hope this helps.  I thought Amazon had free returns. I was charged additional money when I returned my first pair to exchange even though they were the exact same price. All my other Frye boots have been so comfortable from the start ....IF these boots were not on clearance I would send them back again but the discounted price is letting me give them a 3rd chance!  :)

column6: Merrell Men's Waterpro Maipo Water Shoe
column13: Great water/hike shoes for the money!
column14:
The shoes are great EXCEPT, the right one has some threads that have been melted/cut that rub on the top of my right foot. I have attempted to trim/sand it. It is better, but I can still feel it. It really doesn't matter, I wear Keen & Icebreaker wool short socks when I wear them and all is well. I have worn them all day swimming/climbing/walking down creeks for a couple weekends now without an issue. The tread is aggressive, but they will still slip on some slick rocks in the creek bed. It would be nice if the sole was a little more conforming to rocks to make them grip better, but I think they are stiffer to protect your foot. Don't misunderstand, they flex very well for a shoe, they would just grip better if the sole was more pliable. Its hard to find the right configuration; there are always trade-offs for any gain. I have narrow feet and the fit/lace well. Also, unlike cheap water shoes, the sole stays in place when you walk/hike!

All-in-all, these are a great pair of water shoes!

column6: Clarks Women's Whistle August Ankle Boots
column14:
I am a little too excited about these shoes. They just arrived. When I first saw them I was afraid they'd be too small because they're a little shorter than the other shoes I was wearing. But the length is perfect. They are slightly tighter than I'd like in front due to being thin vertically, but I don't think it's a big deal and hope they loosen up once I break them in. They look beautiful. They are noisy and sound heavy on my hardwood floor, but I don't mind too much. Oh! And the best part... I didn't think they were going to be good for dancing when I ordered them but when I started walking the first thing I noticed was that they glide easily. These are going to be fantastic for dancing! I am a partner dancer. I bought these for work, but now I am afraid they're too nice! But for the price, I could order another pair easily. I'll update if I have any unreasonable problems.

I am normally about 7.5 or anywhere between 7 and 8. I ordered 7.5. This is def the right size. :) the box has a size chart on it which is diff from Amazon. It says US 7.5 and 8.0 = Euro 39.

I am tomboyish and don't normally buy pretty shoes, but these are really pretty without being too feminine for my tastes. Somehow.

Update: After wearing these to work, I have to say they are slightly too small. My little toe is hurting a little because there's very little wiggle room. I'm still hoping that they will break in and be more comfortable. Or my feet will get used to them. My feet are normal width, maybe slightly on the narrow side. These shoes could use slightly more width for me. The thing is, when I am walking, my feet slide to the front of the shoe, and this makes them feel smaller in the front. Also I am wearing mismatched black socks and the left one keeps sliding down on the foot - it doesn't do that with any of my other shoes. If anyone knows of any socks that don't slide down with these shoes, please let me know!

I still give it 5 stars because these are great for the price and the wrong size isn't exactly their fault. If I were to order another pair, I might order size 8 or 7.5W. I don't plan on sending these ones back as it's too much trouble and the sizing on these so far isn't too bad.ong size isn't exactly their fault. column6: adidas Performance Women's A.T. 360 Control Weightlifting Trainer Shoe
column13: I find them far more comfortable than running shoes
column14: I use these shoes in the gym during my weight training workouts and HIIT exercise. I find them far more comfortable than running shoes, but not as geared toward weight training specifically. These are more of a cross trainer shoe than a lifting shoe, so if buying specifically for squats I would skip these; however, if you are like me and don't want to lug multiple pairs of shoes to the gym for each workout, these are great for short length HIIT and supportive for weights. I do use these during all weight exercises, including squats and they are significantly more stable than standard running/walking shoes and were more affordable than chucks (which many people use, but I find uncomfortable for HIIT). They had a bit more space in the toe area than I was used to but I decided to keep them rather than size down and I actually find it comfortable and it leaves room for a shoe insert. These come with a sort of memory foam interior and mine had a small crease in one side that was very uncomfortable. I like to use arch supports in my shoes so I just covered the insert with an additional arch support and they are perfect!

column14:
I like sunglasses, I spend a good deal of time outside, and have fairly sensitive eyes. These are excellent sunglasses for the money. They seem well made, are reasonably sturdy and are cheap enough that you don't need to treat them as precious. If (like my wife) you find yourself constantly loosing sunglasses, or throwing them in your purse/glovebox/cup holder where they get scratched, these are great because when they are (inevitably) lost or damaged you can just buy a new pair.

The glasses are light, and comfortable to wear, and do a good job cutting out the light. The frames seem well made and are reasonably durable (especially for the price). All in all, a great pair of cheap sunglasses. I received this product at a discount in exchange for my honest review.

column6: Coleman Women's CC1 6024 Polarized Sunglasses Audrey Hepburn Style
column13: Great fit, style and no glare, polarized lenses make all the difference.
column14:
I purchased these in tortoise, although it was a hard decision between those and burgundy. I am very picky when it comes to sunglasses. They really have to fit well or I won't wear them, so I was a little worried about buying them without getting to try them on, but these are so nice and fit so well. They don't pinch behind your ears ( I get a headache from that) , yet they are tight enough so they don't fall forward when you bend over. The polarized lenses make all the difference in the world. I have adrenal problems and it causes my eyes to be very sensitive to the glare from the sun. It's not always a problem, but sometimes when I'm driving and the sun is really bright , I have to squint so much that my eyes are almost closed....especially when there are a lot of cars around to reflect the sun. With polarized lenses, the glare is not just diminished, but eliminated. So for me, it's not just about finding a pair that I like the way they look and fit, but if they have polarized lenses. These check off all of those marks for me. I love them.
I received a discount to purchase these in exchange for an honest review....and they are awesome !!

column6: OOFOS OOriginal Thong Sandal - Unisex Black - Men's 11 / Women's 12
column13: Great comfort, but the thong won't hold up. Buy the slide.
column14: 2/1/16 Product update. The thong broke today! I was worried about the durability of that little piece of foam. I would NOT recommend these shoes even though Oofos customer service replaced them for me under warranty. The warranty is only 6 months and they would not exchange for the slide due to their warranty policy. There is no reinforcement in the thong. She also told me the shoes were only designed for about a 6 month life - if you are wearing daily.   Update 8/25//15. I definitely have been more willing to be more active with these shoes. The soreness has subsided somewhat, but there is no question the extra activity is contributing. Obviously, the goal was met  - I am more active in these shoes than I am in other shoes thanks to the support and comfort. The only question is, when will I be able to buy OOFOS dress and casual shoes with full leather uppers? They are probably too squishy to work well as active/athletic purposes.  Update 8/14. I lowered the review to 4 stars. My feet are a bit sore. I am not sure why, perhaps due to a bit more activity. These are still by far the most comfortable shoes I have ever owned. However, I am concerned these aren't good for my plantar fasciitis. I will update the review in a few weeks to report any updates.  Original entry 8-10. Wow! I just got my Oofos yesterday and already I miss them!! I am at work, and unfortunately, I can't wear sandals with my suit. But if I could I would! These shoes are THAT GOOD! I have chronic plantar fasciitis and have tried everything except invasive surgery. Hopefully these shoes will make it more bearable. My Croc Comfort Clouds have been the best I have found, and I remember being very happy when I first got them. But they are EXTREMELY HOT look horrible, so I don't wear them much. I will update my review, hoping the joy continues.  I wish Oofos made inserts and/or casual and dress shoes. I will be FIRST on the list to buy! For now, I will wear my Oofos at every opportunity. I will begin a walking program powered by Oofos! I have been unable to walk much due to the pain, but I am hopeful these shoes help me get more active - which obviously will help with the overall condition.

column6: Tretorn Men's Gunnar Canvas-M
column13: perfect fit. Just measure your foot in millimeters and ...
column14: Google Images has a Tretorn conversion chart. Measure your foot with a measuring tape in millimeters and ignore whatever else you would normally use as an indicator. My first pair was ordered online, and since I wear a US9, that's what I ordered. Apparently, Tretorn's US9 is a size and half too big for my foot. I wish they would standardize this. Anyway, perfect fit. Just measure your foot in millimeters and you should be good to go. Don't phone it in, either. Really get precise with your measurement for a perfect fit. Only gripe is that they looked like they would have a slightly green tint to them, but it's really grey under normal lighting conditions.

column13: Stunning, Sophisticated, Stylish Bag--and Practical for Travel, Business, or Daily Use
column14: I purchased this tote bag for a trek around France during the Summer.  I am naturally one of those people who carries a book (or two), notebook, pens, and other writing gear around, so I nearly always buy bags to accommodate my reading and writing habits (no Kindle for me--sorry, Amazon!).  In any case, since I also knew I'd be adding travel books, maps, and other "travel" items to my typical bag, not to mention a digital camera, I wanted something a bit more stylish for France and substantial in size for traveling.  I always prefer crossbody bags because they are easier to carry hands-free and are safer than a hand or shoulder bag.  Looking for versatility beyond traveling, I sought a good neutral-color bag that would not clash with any (or many) outfits.  This supple leather bag exceeds my expectations.  From the moment I arrived for pick-up by the travel van, my traveling companions (male and female) raved about this bag.  For ten days, they joked about stealing it when I fell asleep!  What makes it particularly attractive is the zipper that goes around the sides and bottom of the bag; when not packed full of necessities and whatnot, this tote (which looks more like a messenger bag or briefcase) can be zipped closed and used as a briefcase/folder-looking bag.  The sleeker silhouette is quite sophisticated and, overall, this bag and its color-blocked leather (camel and a slightly lighter leather at the top) is both practical and attractive.  Although the shoulder strap is a bit flimsier than I would have liked, it held up (to my surprise) after a week and a half of hauling the bag everywhere.  Finally, I like that, if you really need more room, you can pack the bag and not fold the flaps down over the purse.  This makes the tote a little taller and a bit less sleek or attractive, but if you're traveling home on a plane and simply need more room to stash souvenirs or extra items in your personal carry-on item, it sure comes in handy!  All in all, this bag held up well, is aesthetic perfection, will be versatile and useful for any kind of wardrobe, and is sure to make you the envy of the crowd.

column6: Wolverine Men's Mckay Metatarsal Guard Boot
column13: Good boot for the price, weak link is insole and lining.
column14:
The is the second pair of these boots I have purchased. The first purchased at a brick and mortar store in Davenport Iowa. The second from Amazon, so I knew exactly what size to get. In the vast majority of shoes I wear a 9 1/2 medium width, in some brands that bumps to a 10. In cases were there is only whole sizes I go 10. In winter boots with thick socks, 10...you get the point. For the Wolverines I purchased a 9 1/2 and they fit almost perfectly. Four stars for the following issues. Until you get them really broken in you can plainly feel the internal metatarsal plate rub the top of your foot. The tongue is also not very flexible, probably to keep the met guard in place, but it makes donning and doffing the boot a little more tricky. The last point leads to this one. After a few months of wear I pulled my foot out and the internal heel area of the boot and its liner came out. I tried all the things one does to make the boot last a little longer, glue, duct tape, silicon....etc nothing could be done.
So why did I buy again? Simply for price.
Some people like to buy a much more expensive boot and then take it to a cobbler for a resole and new foot beds. I have done that before and gave it up. You spend $200 on a boot, get 6 months to a year before repairs are needed then you pay a cobbler $35 for a resole, $20 for insoles and $5 for laces and you still have the same smelly old boot but with new gear. For less money I can buy 2 new pairs of boots. I use a system of 4 pairs of boots, I have two metguards when needed and two regular steel toes. Simply rotate through the week. The boots get time to dry and recover and my boots last YEARS this way. When one gets too ratty, dispose and replace. Yes I spend money on boots, but my feet are part of my job and my comfort at work is worth it to me. 4 pairs of boots $500- $600, never having sore feet, legs, hips, back issues or putting on swampy feeling boots in the morning....Priceless. It works well even with a 2 boot rotation, but I digress.....
Brings us back to this boot. Amazon total with shipping $110. My first pair lasted well over two years in my rotation. I rarely work only eight hours and I am on my feet all day in a wide variety of places from construction sites, to factories. I would project that the boot would last about a year if I wore it daily. The weak link is the insoles and internal lining. When I tossed out that 1st pair the sole still had tons of life, the toe had not worn through despite lots of time kneeling and scuffing of the toe. The leather and stitching was still fully intact and I had replaced the laces only once. I had also replaced the insoles with a decent quality pair after the 1st year in rotation. So overall it was a great boot. I actually felt bad throwing it out, but as I said, there was no repairing the inner lining, and God knows I tried to eek out a few more months of service. So I do recommend it, especially if you need met guards at your workplace. They are comfortable after break in and the sole wears slowly. They are on the heavy side, but I'd expect that with the met guard and the thick long lasting sole. Do not buy for hiking or hunting!!! They are made in Bangladesh. I have never dropped heavy stuff on my toes, so I cannot speak to its protective abilities nor do I want to find out. I assume they will offer the advertised level of protection.

column13: Great light travel purse, but the zippers are a pain.  UPDATE 4 months later below.
column14: This purse is terrific.  There are so many ways to organize.  It's incredibly light.  You can make it very very long if you'd like.  There's only one thing I don't like about it and it's really making me crazy and it's the reason I'm going down to 3 stars:  the zippers.  There are plenty of zippers on this purse and two of them are very difficult to close.  My daughter had to hold the teeth close together while I moved the zipper.  I'm hoping that if we do that enough it will work itself out, but it's really a drag.  Sometimes I get so frustrated that I don't even close the zippers all the way.  But... in every other way this is a great purse so I don't want to return it.  I know... I'm crazy.  UPDATE:  I bought this purse in July and the zippers were very difficult.  It is now November and one of the zippers has actually broken off.  I downgraded my rating to 2 stars for a few reasons:  Yes, it continued to be too difficult zipping and unzipping, so much so that the zipper broke.  2) someone else mentioned this and I didn't think it was a big deal but it actually is a pain... the metal rings on the sides of the purse which hold the strap turn and twist the strap and it looks terrible.  It's impossible to get the strap to stay on the rings the way they should.  I have just bought a Baggalini purse that is similar and we'll see how that goes. So far no problems with zippers and there's no way the strap can move off the rings because it's sewn too close to the rings.  I'm sure that doesn't make sense until you've bought this purse.

column6: Teva Women's Zirra Sandal
column14: These sandals are definitely the cutest of their kind. I use the word "cute" lightly. However, I bought the sandals for some serious hiking in Hawaii and they just don't provide the comfort I am looking for. Let me preface this by explaining that I don't have problematic feet or orthopedic issues, just needed a sandal that I could hike miles in through dry and wet land. Because the straps are so thin, the area around the ankle is unlined like other chunkier Teva sandals, and I found that sans lining, they rubbed a bit where the straps join. This won't do, as I'm hoping to actually avoid blisters. Unfortunately, these beauties are going back and I'm gonna have to settle for their uglier but more practical sister. I'm going with the Teva Terra Fi Lite instead as I've tried them on in stores and can attest to their comfort and support. Hope this review helps as I was confused by the stellar reviews on this sandal but finally figured out that the discomfort around the ankle was due to the lack of lining where the straps join. Too bad.

There are 4 inside pockets and two deep outside pockets perfect for water bottles, everything is cotton lined. I give this 4 stars just because other reviewers are right, the shoulder strap is obviously a different color since it's made from a different material. Also, I feel the bag handles are very flimsy to hold the weight of this bag when it's filled. You would have to store this bag by sitting it on its bottom or by hanging with the provided shoulder strap, you would not be able to store it by hanging it by the bag handles in my opinion. This bag looks so cute and cool and awesome and I'm so sorry I'm being redundant. (!)<br /><br />Okay but in all seriousness this bag is perfect for my needs right now and possibly forever. Its a 9" x 9" circle with an 11.5" zippered opening. both and outer and inner-zipping pocket and 2 inner smart phone-sized slot pockets. The strap is fully adjustable from 53.5" at its longest and 28" at shortest. Also at 3.5" wide it's a lot more spacious than I was expecting and holds all my daily items with a bit of room for any unexpected extras. The inner and outer zip pockets are 5.25" wide by 5.5" deep. The two slot pockets are your average smart phone size.<br /><br />Unfortunately after only a week or so of use the part that rests (and rubs) against my hip has worn off a little ink. I haven't noticed it on any of my clothing but its sad to watch it go from the bag. So keep in mind that any area constantly seeing abrasive wear is probably gonna wear off. My beloved catfish friend and every other part of the bag is perfectly fine.<br /><br />All in all I still really like this bag, I also think it's really cool that they are hand made in the US out of recycled fish feed (rice, etc) bags. I want to buy more but I also never want to stop using this one, ya know? I've added some (be it poor quality cell phone) pictures too. Hope I was helpful!	2015-08-11

column6: Hoka One Men's Constant Ankle-High Running Shoe
column14:
I've been running for years. Half marathons are what I enjoy. My favorite shoes for several years were Mizuno Nirvanas, which are unfortunately discontinued now. I've tried Mizuno Inspires, Asics Kayanos, and Brooks Adrenalines trying to find that next best shoe.

As a runner well into my 40s, I like the idea of something with more cushioning that the Hokas provide. However, I overpronate and a support shoe works best for me. Hoka never had that before the Constant.

I have a love-hate relationship with these shoes.

Things I love:
- The ride and cushioning is fantastic. My knees, hips, and back don't seem to get as beat up on longer runs when I'm wearing these.
- The low heel-toe drop makes my muscles work differently. I like it, but it does take a little getting used to.

What I don't love:
- Blisters. I get blisters on the outside of both big toes. Tried a 10.5 and it was too little. Went to an 11 and still get them, although not as bad. This has never been a problem in other shoes. Even my best socks and generous body glide on the offending area is not enough to stave off the blisters. The hot spots show up at 3-4 miles. Furthest I've dared run with these is 6 miles.

I wish they worked for me. I want them to work. I love the ride, but just can't deal with the blisters. My experiment with Hokas has been a failure, but your mileage may vary.

column6: Altra Men's Superior 2 Running Shoe
column13: Poor warranty/customer service, great shoe to start, failed to last more than 200 miles.
column14: I have had two pairs now both with about 200 miles on them before I found them worn out and not useful for running in. They started out great, fast, light, great traction, good cushioning. The problem is that after running in them for around 200 miles they lost all of their cushioning and support, both with the foam in the sole and the insole themselves. They were so packed out and smashed that I had to stop running in them from leg fatigue and pain. I am not a heavy person, 165lbs, so I shouldn't be able to destroy a shoe that fast. I called to have them considered a warranty issue since Altra says you should get 300-500 miles out of them. I was told that I first had to send them back to the place I purchased them. Shouldn't it be the manufacturers responsibility to fix a problem with their product, not the store selling them? I purchased them from a brick and mortar store 500 miles from where I live and it isn't that stores responsibility to fix Altra's problems. Second, they said if it was after 30 days (Now, I actually put 200 miles on a pair of shoes in 30 days, but I would guess most people don't.) Altra could only offer you 25% off of a new pair purchased directly from them. Anybody paying full retail price from the manufacturer is overpaying because with the internet you should be able to find a reduced price somewhere, so offering me a coupon for 25% off only good at their website doesn't save me money, and on top of that doesn't get me a warranty. I was told to purchase them from a store that offered returns on items after Altra's 30 day policy expired. I would love to keep running in them, but there is no way I can afford $110 or even $82.50 for as many pairs of shoes I need for my training.

column6: ASICS Men's GT 2000 2 Running Shoe
column13: these are very comfortable shoes, lightweight
column14:
These were my first real running shoe. I've got about 250 miles on the pair now, so I feel I can give an experienced review overall. These are dedicated running shoes for me, no other usage aside from warm up walks and street running - asphalt, concrete, very rarely grass when I have to skirt around puddles or slippery pavement. I only ran in the rain a couple of times.

First, quickly, these are very comfortable shoes, lightweight, and stylish. I trained up to a 5k (3.1 miles) without any issues aside from 1 little section of mesh on the left shoe spontaneously disappearing/breaking. Not sure how that happened, but it did. It has not gotten worse over 100 miles or so, which speaks highly of their mesh quality I suppose. Could have snagged something I suppose.

When I got past 3.1 miles consistently, that's when I started to get a case of plantar fasciitis in my right foot, and the right side of my foot (outer edge) started to bug me. Not sure if I'm just dealing with a shoe that is 1/2 size too small or something (my foot feels great in it, before running, during and after). But, it's interesting to note that as my distance increased (very gradually) and these shoes are aging, something has changed.

I also noticed a tear above the left big toe, in the fabric layer under the mesh. It's about 1/2 inch now, but I expect that will grow. And gradually my toe will probably poke through the mesh - before that happens, I intend to retire this pair for a new pair shortly and use these for walking.

So, I expect to get about 250-300 miles out of this pair of shoes. I've read you can usually get around 400 miles out of a shoe, but that's probably a general guideline and lots of factor come into play - your personal stride/gait/wear patterns, surfaces you run on, etc.

Aside from the unexpected wear above the toe, the random mesh fraying, and plantar fasciitis in my right foot (which honestly I can't attribute to the shoe necessarily, but it's worth noting), I do enjoy how these shoes feel on my feet and while running. I may get another pair (perhaps a little bigger) or I might try another brand...haven't decided.

column6: Rocky Men's RKC042 Military and Tactical Boot
column14: There are a lot of comments on the tan version of these boots, both good and bad. Overall I am pleased with my boots. They are made of high-quality leather, as opposed to the C4T predecessors.  It does add a bit of weight, but the durability is worth it (not to mention they are actually AR670-1 compliant).  They have great insoles and are very comfortable right away. That being said, there is one negative comment that comes up over and over again: the boots pinch on the top of the foot.  When I first put them on, one pinched, one didn't. Upon a simple examination, I discovered that the pinch is because the seam was folded over where the tongue meets the rest of the boot on the top of the feet. A little bit of care when putting the boots on, and loosening them a lot solves this problem. Nevertheless, I shouldn't have to loosen my laces all the way each time I put the boots on. This is very obviously a flaw that could be easily fixed by Rocky in the future, and I hope they do so. If not for that, these boots would get 5 stars.

The shoes did really well all evening and were fairly comfortable for me.  I did take a pair of sandals to wear while dancing because I am clumsy and heels and me dancing don't mix.  These are a super classic looking heel and I would love to pick up a few more pairs.  They seem to be really well made as well.  They fit me very true to size, and I wear a size 9.  I would highly recommend the Riverberry Gaby Fashion Stiletto heels for everyone! I received this product at a promotional price in exchange for my unbiased review. All opinions are my very own.

column13: Great!  Do NOT store in HOT places!
column14: I have developed a foot problem due to a long bone in my foot.  Arrgh - I am very active and this "benched" me for a bit.  The Dr. said there is no cure and to look for cushion, arch support and a shoe that allows my toes to stay in their natural position - think no squished toes.  These are great!  I wear them all of the time!  When they stretch (they do a bit from time to time) out I put them in the dryer for a BIT and wear them immediately.  Do NOT leave these in a hot car.  The photo shoes 2 pair of size 8 - the 2 shoes in the middle are the pair that I left in a hot car for a day - the far left and far right shoe are the normal size.  You can see the effects of heat - it took several wearings with multiple layers of socks to get the shoes back to my size.

column13: He said that it is the best pair of winter boots he has ever owned
column14:
Bought these for my husband, who is always working on the farm and out in the sub zero temps. He said that it is the best pair of winter boots he has ever owned.

Now getting a compliment out of my husband, with that high of a rating, is a flat out miracle. He never likes anything and always has a complaint, but with these boots, no complaints of any kind.

He did say that if you are in weather, above 50*, that you may have to unzip them, to let your feet breathe and cool down. They are exceptionally made and very good looking boots, on. Not too thick, that his jeans won't go over the top of them, to wear on the outside of his boots. Even better when the jeans are tucked in and no issues with the upper being tight, if the jeans are tucked in.

If you work outdoors, in the frigid temps, I recommend getting these. Your toes and feet will feel like they are on the beach, when it's -11* outside.

column6: Chippewa Men's 9\ Waterproof Insulated Steel Toe EH 25420 Logger Boot"
column13: God fired the royal boot maker because Chippewa makes better boots.
column14:
Here's the deal. I wear my boots for 12-14 hours a day, every day. I walk an average of 6-8 miles per day for work, on surfaces ranging from concrete and asphalt to snow, through streams, and over pipeline right-of-way. I honestly wear my boots every single day, walking 7 miles per day, (on average according to the pedometer on my phone,) and I usually get about 2 years out of a pair of Super Loggers.
I've owned lots of Red Wings, I've owned Rockys and Carolinas, and I guarantee you that Chippewa Super Loggers are the best boots money can buy. I wouldn't give a plugged nickel for a pair of Red Wings, and I'll never own another pair of Rockys. I'm 6'4" and 275 lbs, and if a guy my size can get 4500-5000 miles of walking out of a pair of boots, well that's pretty impressive.
They are as waterproof as a pair of muck boots (albeit not as tall,) and they're made in the USA. Now, if you want a pair of work boots because you want to look tough in front of your buddies, then go buy a 50 dollar pair at Wal-Mart; but if you're one of those guys, (like I used to be,) who never found a boot that was tough enough, then look no further. Think about how much money your old lady spends on her shoes. Do you think she ever walked 5000 miles in a pair of them? I don't think so. If you wear your boots all day every day, then these are a bargain at twice the price. Stop reading this and buy these boots!

column6: New Balance Men's M670V1 Running Shoe
column13: Great looking shoe, with maximum support. must go a size up.
column14:
New Balance M670 are very comfortable shoes. Those that bought these shoes at regular size made a huge mistake. I'm regularly a twelve in other shoes. Yet I know with this amazing brand you must go up one size. These shoes are very well cushioned. I work in a warehouse, so I'm on concrete all day long. These shoes make it so I have much less foot and ankle pain. The absorb heel support technology is great for those that need extra support for their feet. Throw in some aftermarket insoles, and you have got yourself a wonderful shoe.

I own 3 other pairs of New Balance, and these are the best I have bought yet. I love all of my New Balance. Yet I would say as far as looks, and support combined these bad boys take the cake.

New Balance gets my money also because most of their shoes are assembled in the USA. I have these M670s in the Blue and green. What a well designed shoe. Not to mention I payed 24 bucs total on amazon prime. These shoes are 75 bucs at every store, and every other online site.
