column13: You can't ever go wrong with O.G or Bonnie!
column14: This is my second pair of beautiful Bonnie boots (thanks to a 3 mo.old German Shepard whose chewing habit is at least eqdual to my O.G. habit) and my 8th pair of Old Gringos. The leather is super supple but sturdy (my puppy can vouge for this) they are a bit snug when you first get them but stretch.and form to your foot from.the first time you wear them. These were are my all time favorite boots (coming from someone who owns no less than 40 pairs) they are comfortable right out of the box although I always add a padded insert which guarantees all day and night comfort and they go with everything!  My favorite is with a  little western fees as but I have yet to wear them with anything and not get stopped/complimented multiple times. I oil all of my boots that are not suede to protect them from weather and would recommend anyone else to for extended life. The one negative with O.G. is the soles wear quickly, for such an expensive boot I would expect more (I don't have this problem with my Lucchese or Frye boots) but O.G. is so far ahead of the game in style  they are and continue to be my favorites even with what I see as flaws. They are expensive, but your worth it! You will love these boots. I would buy your regular size, I always have and they always fit great. I do add an insert but the leather will.warm and stretch to your foot.

column6: Caterpillar Men's Crossrail Steel Toe Work Boot
column13: Another solid choice for factory work
column14:
I've been through a couple pairs of Steel Toe boots over the years and I keep coming back to Caterpillar boots. They typically take a week or so to break in, but after that these boots feel just great! These Crosstrails have a great sole that flexes just where it should. I feel more balanced on ladders and concrete. I work in a factory so I'm forever climbing on and over machinery. Never once have I stumbled in these boots. I say this because my previous pair of cheap boots just felt odd with how I walk and move around. These Caterpillar's are dammed near perfect!

My only beef is that I always have to replace the insoles. This is not just Caterpillar, but ALL boots I've purchased. I don't get why after spending so much money I always have to spend just a bit more for insoles. But comfort is key after working 40 plus hours on my feet all week. These insoles are flabby material when you pull them out. If you have high arches, get an insole to support them.

Another note. The bottom of the box says 'Wolverine' on the bottom. Sounds to me like Caterpillar and Wolverine are sharing footwear designs.

column6: Mizuno Women's Wave Enigma 5 Running Shoe
column13: Great for Walking, Running, or Prancercising!
column14:
Mizuno is not a household name for us.... we are big on Adidas, Nike, UnderArnour, etc. so when these came up on Vine I was excited to have my family try something new and different.

Upon arrival I was immediately impressed with the build quality of these shoes; excellent design and workmanship and the detailing of the differing materials combine for a great look.

I originally ordered for my older daughter however upon trying on discovered that these were easily a full size too small... uh-oh... Plan B: called in my younger daughter (9) and let her try them on and they fit well! A little on the big side for her bit for a running shoe you want the extra area for foot expansion (I am no guru here but I was told by a runner at a running store in my area that shoes used for running need to be at least 1 size larger to accommodate for foot expansion upon landing) so these were right there.

Immediately she commented on the lightness of the shoes as well as the bounciness of the sole. Quite a bit of cushioning in the heel and forefoot areas. There is also a medium-wide toe box allowing her little toes to remain wiggly and unbound.

To the track.. or, rather, sidewalk. First walk and run went fine. Plenty of support and stability for the flats, hills, and corners. All OK on these fronts.

Once we had put these through the paces I had my daughter give these shoes the ultimate test: PRANCERCISE. Yes, I had my daughter prancercise (Google it) down the street.... she had fun, I smiled, and the shoes held up to that physical abuse!

All in I would definitely get these again. Great styling, design, and construction. There is some issue with sizing so buyer beware in this and ensure that if you buy here you have free returns... just in case. Prancercise on!!

column13: A little too slim fitting for me...
column14:
These are great shoes by just looking at them, they have the wonderful hard rubber throughout the whole sole that means you don't lose the tread on them within the first 3 months. But this pair were just a little too snug on each side of my upper foot in the toe area, though to be fair, my feet are on the wider side. I can wear normal sizes in many styles but some are just too narrow. The length seemed like it could be fine but it was hard to tell with the tightness on the sides.

I can't go up half a size due to having a size 11 women's foot, but I just ordered a 11W to see if the wide version might fit better and make them wearable.

I love Skechers as a brand and while I love the D'Lites line, I hate the foam like inner sole that wears out too quickly. The Sports line has the better more durable sole that I need as someone who is walking around all day long, everyday (as a nanny) and so I really hope that the wides will fit great. I have 4 other styles and another (as well as the Sports Energy) on the way. I have been wearing nothing but Skechers since 2003 and I absolutely love them.

column14:
Aviator style sunglasses are my absolute favorite and when I saw that these came with my favorite color "Pink!" lenses I was so happy!

This is a great feature for me because my daughter will often grab my sunglasses off of my face and this ends up with lots of broken glasses. I've been wearing the glasses for nearly a week and so far no scratches and I'm still absolutely in love with them. They even came with a protective bag and microfiber cleaning cloth.

column6: Baggallini Luggage Traverse Backpack
column14: This is by far the best all- around bag (sling, cross- body, backpack) I've purchased.  I have numerous Baggalini products and love them all! The designers for Baggalini actually know what women like in their bags/ purses.  If I see the name Baggalini I generally take a deeper look at the product. I've actually purchased this bag in a large variety of colors.  For ages, I looked for a bag that would be lightweigt (as I have a poor back)  and durable.  This bag is it. The purchaser would have the option of using a wallet, as there is an area to hold credit cards on the inside.  Also, it has pockets for pens, a phone, and an inside zippered area for security. It comes with a detachable zippered bag, as well. The zippered bag can be removed and the hook can be used for keys.  The larger outside pocket I use for a variety of items, such as a comb, mirror, keys, etc.  It's actually a spacious area that can hold quite a number of items without bulking the backpack.  The two smaller pockets on the outside are perfect for smaller items.  Probably one of the greatest ideas that needs to be imperative in designing bags is making the lining of the bags a light color, versus a dark black or brown. As we age, those dark inside colors make it nearly impossible to locate anything in the bag.  Baggalini has resolved this issue. All the bags I purchased have a lighter inside lining... love it.  I'm thinking there would be no reason why this bag couldn't be washed, as well. However, I haven't had the need wash it yet.  It is just the perfect all around bag!

column6: KEEN Utility Men's PTC Slip On Work Shoe
column14:
I purchased these for my dad. Both of us have "wide" feet, but that is only partly true. Our feet are a little wide, but our feet never get narrower at the toe. I've worn a keen half-hiking boot for 2 years now and found their shoe design to be perfect for my feet. My dad has typically had to buy shoes with EEE (triple width) and a little too long to give his toes room to be "wide" (I consider it normal!). With these, he ordered the size he should wear (9.5) and the shoes fit perfectly. It's a dream to have shoes designed that do not cramp your toes or come to a ridiculously narrow point.

He's been wearing these to work outside (farm work, moving furniture, ... active outdoor work) and absolutely loves them.

column6: Enzo Angiolini Women's Pamla Bootie
column13: A little narrow, but overall a great Bootie!
column14:
I LOVE ankle boots, and obviously I love leopard print. Also, love a bargain, and I nabbed a size 7 at a great price. What's not to adore about these?
Here's my thoughts on the Pamla Bootlie.
These seem to run a little narrow. Since the boots are made of leather (at least partially) I expect them to be able to stretch and break in.
The heel is high, yes. If you're not used to wearing 3" or 4" heels, this may not be the shoe for you. The fact that this is a bootie does make it easier to walk in them, though - if you're on the fence.
The ankle strap is kind of weird. An odd design choice, but I like it. It adds that "something extra" to what would otherwise be a plain pair of boots. It would have been awesome if the strap was removable but unfortunately it's attached at the back. The strap does feel odd, and you'll want to flex your foot while doing it up, otherwise you may find it digging in as you sit or drive. You do get used to it though!
My only issues are the narrow width, and the print. Everyone's idea of the perfect leopard print is different (Ivanka Trump's shoes have the BEST, IMO) but the print on these seems a little...messy? However, I am quite happy with my new leopard print ankle boots! I've gotten several compliments already.

column6: Business Golf Eyeglasses Genuine Wood Sunglasses with Bamboo Case- Z6069
column13: Very cool Glasses that Work Well and are a Great Value.
column14:
Very well made and stylish glasses. Lens and frame are bamboo with an aluminum insert for strength that helps keep the frame thinner and sleeker looking. The Inside has a beautiful rich teak colored wood tone. The arms have spring hinges that work well and have a flexible rubber portion for the ears. The front of the frame and the arms are stained black but the grain still is visible if you look closely. The side view has a very cool look with the inside wood tone, bright white/silver of the aluminum and the dark front face.
The lenses are polarized as described. I have a fairly large head and these fit me well with the flexible frame but they also fit my petit wife well and looked good on her too. Lenses are slightly larger than the lenses for the Ray-Ban Wayfarer's that I replaced. I wasn't sure about the larger size at first but have adjusted. These are still unique and you don't see many out there which I like.

These are very well built for the money. I would love to have a pair where the entire frame, except for the ear portion, was the same look and tone of the back side of the frame. Those would be very cool glasses and I would definitely buy a pair if they were in the same price range or even slightly higher.

column13: My picky sons love these! We have tried some other flip flops ...

The straps are a soft double layer nylon that contacts the foot. The nylon in between the toes is very soft, supple and non-chaffing. The sole is a firm foam with a non-marking, non-slip base. column6: Altra Men's Lone Peak 2.5 Trail Running Shoe
column13: Good shoe with a few flaws, less than ideal customer support.
column14:
I have run about 180 miles in my pair in about 3 weeks and have a few detractors to list. First, the sole is coming unglued from the foam. Second, the lugs seem to not be very sturdy as I am missing parts of a few and most show more wear than I feel like they should at less than 200 miles. Third, the mountain laminated picture on the outside of the shoe is peeling off. Fourth, this shoe is sized larger than previous models, so you would need to size a half size down. Fifth, because it is wide, turning sharp corners at speed causes my foot to tip off of the edge of the shoe because there isn't much lateral stiffness in the upper.

Now some good: Much lighter and faster feeling then the previous models. Cushioning is very good and smooths out rocky trails very well. Traction is great (until the lugs come off). Overall the fit is nice and having a soft upper really lets my foot expand as needed. No blisters or hot spots with these shoes.

Final thoughts: Again, durability and sizing seem to elude Altra. If it wasn't for the wide toe box and solid trail features, I would look at different brands. Their customer service is poor, and there isn't any help with the "warranty" unless you purchase shoes from them directly, which in most cases cost you an extra 20% over what you would pay elsewhere. It would be nice to see them stand up for their product and make it right by an unsatisfied customer.

column6: Ryka Womens Prelude Walking Shoes
column13: I have been disappointed by two purchases lately
column14: I have been a fan of Ryka for several years.  However, I think my patronage of this company has come to an end.  I have been disappointed by two purchases lately, including this one.  The problem for me is the cushioning particularly in the heel area.  After just an hour or two on a hard surface, like a city sidewalk, I start to feel discomfort in my heel, leg and/or hip.  It's the lack of sufficient cushion and shock absorption in these shoes.  I did not have this problem with Ryka shoes I purchased years ago (or with other brand shoes for that matter).  But this is the second pair of Rykas that has caused me this problem.  It's too late to return them.  But my lesson is learned.  This will likely be my last purchase of Ryka athletic wear.

column6: adidas Performance Women's Powerblaze W Running Shoe
column13: I have less than perfect knees and become keenly aware of the lack of ...
column14: For the price I paid on Amazon, I have no complaints. But here are a few quick points: The shoes run true to size but I think some feel they run large because the toe box is wide; there is very little arch support; while the shoes are very lightweight, there is little to no cushioning. column13: Does NOT fit like Originals Men's SL 72
column14:
These shoes are comfortable and stylish.

Interestingly these shoes do not fit like these SL 72 shoes: http://www.amazon.com/Adidas-SL-Mens-Running-Shoes/dp/B00G4BU9BO

The linked to SL 72 shoes lean significantly to the inside. I've bought two pairs of the linked SL 72s and they both lean a bit to the inside.

The item being sold here does not lean to the inside, which I prefer.

A big downside of these shoes is that Adidas will certainly either discontinue them quickly, or at least Adidas will again keep the name and redo the sneaker making unwary buyers buy something different from last purchase (kind of like ROM sneaker from 2005 which became more like SAMBA sneaker a few years back). It's already confusing that there are two sneakers with different fits that are both named SL 72. But even worse is when Adidas will cancel and not say what new sneaker fits like this one. Great manufacturing, great quality, good prices, awful marketing.

column6: Refresh Women's Sweater Cuff Lace Up Combat Boots
column14:
I decided to buy these boots as my official first set of combat boots. I did a lot of research and consulted the reviews for multiple sets of boots, and I finally decided upon these for the fact that they were incredibly cheap, looked cute, and seemed like they have good traction. I've only had them for a few days, but they seem to be holding up pretty well so far. The quality is pretty good, but I might need to buy new shoelaces because the one's that come with the boots are not long enough to lace all the way up, not to mention waxy and don't stay tied. I LOVE the faux leather; it is so much easier to tend to and anything that gets on the boots will wipe off easily! The boots are also a little big, but I find that as a positive because I can wear wool socks with them once it gets chilly enough. Right now, they're not comfortable enough to warrant all day wear, but I believe it's because I haven't broken them in yet. Now all I need to do is figure out how to make my super clunky footsteps lighter so I can walk in these boots correctly. ;P

Overall, I would recommend them to someone who wants boots that have good traction, and are fashionable and cheap. I might update in a few months to see how they hold up to wear-and-tear, but for right now I'm a satisfied customer!

column6: Duduma Yellow Night Vision Polarized Sunglasses Glasses for Driving Fishing Shooting Multicolor Frame Uv400 (black frame with yellow lens)
column13: They will help you see better when driving at night
column14:
I am a huge fan of Duduma Sunglasses, they are the best I have ever tried, and the Yellow Night Vision Polarized sunglasses did not disappoint me! I have a huge problem driving at night, as I have night blindness, and the lights from oncoming vehicles make it very difficult for me to see well, so I was very excited to try these out.
They come in a great drawstring bag and a cleaning cloth, which I think is awesome, it helps to maintain them so they will last longer, and keeps the lenses from getting scratched if you toss them in your purse. They have a rounded frame, so they fit perfectly on your head and do not fall, which I have issues with most sunglasses doing this, but not the Duduma.
And the best part is that they work great. It does not cure my night blindness, but it helps immensely. I have an much easier time driving as it takes away the glare from oncoming headlights, which is my biggest issue. Unfortunately, I lost my pair, as my daughter's boyfriend decided to take them when they were driving home from visiting us, but since they were driving at night, and he had my daughter, I was happy to gift them to him ;)
I highly recommend these, they will help you see better when driving at night.
I was provided a sample for free to review and and share my unbiased opinion, I am not affiliated with this company or compensated in any way. I am just a regular Amazon customer who shops a lot on Amazon and enjoys sharing my experiences with others so that they can make an informative buying decision.

column13: The Grey Tango is more like a Taupe
column14:
Starting off with the color, the "Grey Tango" is not gray. It falls somewhere more towards a dark taupe. If you are wearing anything gray color, the shoe looks brown. If you pair it with a taupe or tan, the shoe leans towards a dark gray...almost. The shoe is sort of an undefinable color and essentially they matched nothing I wanted to wear them with. The would probably be more practical in black.

They also run a half size too small - short in the toe. I knew this up front so I ordered a 9 instead of my usual 8.5. I have a medium width but with the 1/2 size up they did gap a little on the sides when I walked in them. The foot bed was comfortable.

column6: Kamik Men's Nation Camo Hunting Boot
column14:
Product arrived right on time (Tuesday, August 4). I had ordered 2-day shipping so I'd have them for a fishing trip on Wednesday, August 5.
I actually wore the boots for a couple of hours on Tuesday evening, just to get used to them.
Very comfortable. I will say that the fit was a bit tight, due to all of the lining/insulation, but they will stretch out somewhat as I wear them.

During my fishing trip, I hiked approximately 5-1/2 to 6 miles while wearing the boots. It was a wet morning, and the boots kept my feet completely dry. They were comfortable to wear while walking in the woods/across rocks, and they provide good ankle support.

I was unable to determine whether the boots will keep my feet warm in the "dead of winter", but I believe they will. The insulation seems ample, and they are rated to -40 degrees, so I'm confident they'll serve well as winter boots.

column13: ... and I have to say these are the most comfortable boots I have ever owned
column14: I have now had these boots for over 60 days and I have to say these are the most comfortable boots I have ever owned.  They do run a bit large, I ordered a 9.5 but when I got the boots they felt huge. I returned the boots with no problem, other than the $17 return shipping. Ordered 8.5 instead and they fit perfectly. I've now backpacked over 100 miles with these boots. I'm always skeptical about waterproof boots as I have owned a few cheaper pairs that don't keep water out very well. These boots held up to 48 hours of rainy backpacking in Flagstaff and my feet stayed dry the whole time! Make sure you invest in some good socks of course. These boots have great support and great tread. I had great traction hiking uphill in the mud whereas as my buddy kept slipping and getting muddy. They do get a little heavier when wet because the outside soaks up a little water but they are super light to begin with and the inner booty keeps your foot totally dry.  I live in the valley so it gets 100+ degrees daily in the summer and these boots do really well in the summer time. They aren't as hot as I thought they would be since they're waterproof. I wear moisture wicking boot socks by Fox River and at the end of my day working outside my feet are still cool and dry. These boots are simply amazing.

column14: These shoes are a steal. I work in a two story restaurant, so not only am I on my feet for six hours a day and five days a week but I am also running up and down stairs during that time. After getting the shoes broken in, they fit tightly at first for the first week or so but that is to be expected, I found that these shoes never left my feet feeling sore. The only exception were on days I worked doubles (which would be roughly ten hours), but to be fair it would not  just be my feet that were sore but also most of my body.  They are slightly wide around the calf but not to the extent that it would bother me and I think it ads to the comfort of the shoe, although I would not suggest buying if you are petite and have skinny legs. As for style I like them but I am not in love, after being stretched out they did sag a bit causing them to look a little clunky at the bottom. I would still recommend these shoes for people looking for a boot that will last. I usually destroy boots within three months but I've had these for 5 without any major damage. The photos I posted are not of the boot when they were new but as they are now.

column6: Ariat Men's Hermosa XR 8\ Work Boot"
column14: This is the best boot in the world. This is my third pair and I'll never get another work boot if I can help it.  Buying through Amazon also was the best way to go, least expensive and I did my shopping on this boot. Anyway, the boot looks nice, has great support due to its very solid construction and the soles are truly slip resistant. I wear it all day in the summer it's comfy and all day in the winter trudging through snow in 10 below.  This boot has never let me down. One thing for a buyer to consider and I'm cool with this, is that I have to get a new pair every 8-10 months.  Oh they'll LAST for years but for me after eight months through no fault of the boot or its quality, the leather just stretches and gets too soft to offer that first quality firm support. My feet will be fine for 8 months then they start to hurt again and this is why I think that happens.  Now, I wear the boot ALL the time, so keep that in mind. Also another plus is with other boots I used to put gel inserts in for extra comfort but I realized I don't need to in these.  The foot bed of this boot is so comfy firm and supportable its truly a wonder.  There. That's my review. Sponsor ME Ariat!!!  BRING IT ON!!

column6: Dr. Martens Unisex Wonder Balsam Shoe Polish
column13: Not effective at conditioning but does restore shine
column14: The product fails to include detailed instructions for proper application. Do the shoes need to be cleaned first? How much product do I use? How often should I use it? There is only a short description on the tin: "Apply a small amount of the balsam onto the leather using a sponge. Work well into the seams. Do not use on suede." After some research, I decided to clean my boots with baby wipes and water, then dry them before applying the thinnest layer of shoe polish onto the sponge. I dab the sponge over the boots, spread the balsam out in circular motions, and let the shoes dry. It absorbs quickly in about an hour or two in warm weather. Over time, the black sponge provided in the tin tends to wear down and crumble when going over rougher stitches and seams.  I use Wonder Basalm once a month to restore shine to my smooth black Dr. Martens, which I wear as work boots. I don't think it conditions very well on shoes for heavy duty use--my docs are already cracking at the back ankles and base of toes. Granted, it's not the best quality leather, but the cracking is bad. By "heavy duty use," I mean being on your feet for over 8 hours a day and constantly crouching and bending your feet.

column6: Timberland PRO Men's Hyperion Waterproof XL ST Work Boot
column13: These Boots are Made for Hurtin'
column14:
I hate to say it, but don't buy these boots.

After six months of ten hour days, they never broke in properly. I wear the hell out of my boots as a landscape manager and have never had issues getting work boots to eventually fit. These though, the tongue continued to slide to the side and the interior rivets holding the lace-ups pressed uncomfortably on my instep. It got to the point where they hurt as soon as I put them on and couldn't wear them anymore.

Additionally, they're huge! I feel like Frankenstein's Monster with those big old blocky shoes. I even have to be careful when driving my truck because the sides of the soles flare out and can catch the break or gas pedal.

Finally, they are not as durable as you would expect. Check out my picture! The leather has peeled away from the rubber toe-cap revealing the safety toe underneath. This happened from everyday use. I ended up pulling my beat up "Keen Utility Louisville 6-Inch Steel Toes out of the closet - which are by far the most comfortable boots I have owned. Sure the soles are separating from the leather, but that didn't occur until two years after rough wear. If I could do it over again, I would have bought another pair of the Keens.

Maybe Timberland will get it right after a couple of models, but for now don't buy these.

column6: Olukai Ohana Sandal - Women's
column14:
I've always been someone who can't wear flip flops because I need arch support or my feet hurt almost immediately. This year I was going on multiple beach trips and I needed a pair of tolerable flip flops. I did lots of research online and decided to buy a pair of these. I made the right choice and then some! These are far better then tolerable, they're a pleasure to wear.

Made of obviously high quality materials, these have held up magnificently through a summer of abuse. I imagine they'll survive several more summers. The fit is 100% as expected, I usually wear a 6-6.5 in regular shoes. My research indicated a 6 would suffice here and that was correct. I have really wide feet, but these are wide enough that my pinky toe doesn't hang off the side. The arch support makes for a gloriously comfortable fit, even through long walks. There was no breaking-in period of discomfort, they only got more comfy as they moulded a bit to the shape of my feet.

I bought the mica color first, which is a soft metallic gold strap with a coffee-brown sole and those look good with almost every outfit. I loved them so much, I came back and bought the Java color too. I, already eyeing pair 3!

I paid $46 per pair, but I'd have paid double that for such comfortable summer sandals. You absolutely can't go wrong if you need some flip flops!

column6: LOCS Sunglasses Hardcore Dark Lens 0103 Designer Stylish NEW
column13: Used to be amazingly dark, but something changed when I reordered a new pair and not so dark anymore.
column14:
I am really torn writing this review. I bought a pair November 2014 and I would give them 5 stars hands down. They were SUPER dark and just what I needed. The construction seemed a bit cheaper & flimsy compared to some of my other sunglasses, but they were still durable enough for everyday use and did exactly what I needed them to do. However, I cracked the lens recently--entirely my fault and opted to reorder a new pair (6 Aug 2015). Put them on today and was shocked to find them barely dark and not fitting the 'hardcore black dark lens' as described. I double-checked to make sure I ordered the right pair of replacement sunglasses; the brand and type matched exactly. The only difference I found was the supply vendor--Nov 14: OverStockToyz, Aug 15: palebluedot, both fulfilled by Amazon and shipped Prime.

I'm including 3 comparison pics. In the first, you can see them side by side--original on the left, replacement on the right--and the right side is clearly a lighter tinted lens than the pair on the left. The second photo shows an led flashlight shining through the replacement pair; the third photo uses the same led light on the original pair. The replacement pair allow through substantially more light than the original pair. Unless there were different batches and/or changes in the production process between my original order and the replacement order, I have no idea why they would be so different. I'm in the process of returning the replacement pair and dropping the review to three stars. So much for consistent product quality.

column6: Sega Dreamcast Console
column14: The Dreamcast is the one console that I always keep going back to. It has so many great games. It was way ahead of it's time by having online functionality right out of the box. Unfortunately, SegaNet (the online service provided by Sega) has long since been shut down since 2001. Even though dial-up was largely the primary connection type at that time, online gaming on the Dreamcast was relatively lag free and smooth. I don't know how they pulled that off, but like I said, this console was ahead of it's time. Anyways, I wish the Dreamcast would've lasted longer during it's mainstream days, but there is a reason why it still has a cult following--it's a great console with a unique library of games that stand the test of time.

column6: Thrustmaster T80 RS PS4/PS3 Officially Licensed Racing Wheel
column14:
I have been playing racing sims since gran turismo on ps1 and have always used a controller. Since this is my first wheel I can't compare it to anything else but a controller but my experience with it so far has been great. I have drive club, the crew and project cars. First off, the crew is probably best off sticking with the DS4 but project cars and drive club become a totally different game. For this price range this is a very well built wheel. You can't ask for much but I think its ridiculous that the next step up (t300) costs as much as a PS4.

I was skeptical about not having force feedback but I don't miss it as much as I thought I would. Yes, for a true experience you need it. But it doesn't kill the fun. I am using this on project cars and when you do make sure you check your settings. I even found some recommended settings on forums that helped a great deal.

Like I said, this is my first wheel and if your looking in this price range you probably never had a wheel before either. Its a great entry level. It helps your driving with the right setup and that's all you can ask. The only gripe I have is the USB cord is built into the wheel and is not long enough. This can be corrected with $5 USB extension but if the main cord gets damaged in any way your screwed.

All in all its quality \\\cheap\\\\\" wheel. And if its your first you will love it. If you have the money then grab the t300 for sure but like I said at $400 I think its a steep price. Always remember though, settings, settings, settings. If you don't think it feels right out of the box adjust those settings before leaving a negative comment."

column6: The Elder Scrolls Online
column13: Not Great, But not too bad
column14:
I wasn't very fair in my last review, and after reading several others, I thought I'd re-review this game. I have banked 30hrs or so, created several different characters, and explored the world.

Pros: Questing; although it's very linear, and redundant the quests are fun and rewarding.
Character Development ; Extremely thorough, there are several sets of skill trees that accompany Class, Race, and faction. The creation is very intricate as well.
Crafting: Very intricate and rewarding. Materials are abundant, if you know where to look ;)
Environment: HUGE, MASSIVE, INTIMIDATING. The world of tamriel absolutely comes alive in TESO
Social: if you like online play, YOU.WILL.LOVE.THIS.GAME. if nyou would rather play solo, guess what? Bethesda thought of that and made tons of "SOLO" dungeons you can play alone, or just run in a public dungeon where you don't have to be in a group, but can still benefit from the help of other players.

CONs: Graphics; the graphical environment isn't great, or spectacular, heck it isn't even really good. It's reminiscent of Oblivion, with more detail on the characters and NPCs, but pretty sub-par for a next Gen game.
Tamriel: Now I know I said the world was a PRO, but it is also a con. It can be daunting to see the sheer scope of the world map, and how wide open and big it truly is. This makes following certain paths a little harder as it is easy to get distracted collecting quests to complete.
Merchants: There are dozens of merchants, really they are everywhere, but mostly they carry the same items, and there is no item sorting, so even if you know the type of item you want to look for you have to search the merchant's entire inventory to find said item.

I initially gave this game a bad review, but it has grown on me. I have found that I like questing in Tamreil, I just wish there was an offline option, but that's just my personal preference. Honestly I just hate not being able to pause a game. The server will also log you out after twenty minutes of inactivity e.g I had to poo, I brought up the menu and went to take care of business , when I got back to the game the menu was still up, as soon as I exited the menu the game logged me out due to "inactivity" kind of annoying. All in all ESO is good enough to warrant Four Stars, but I think the fifth star will be reserved for an offline campaign mode.hate not being able to pause a game. The server will also log you out after twenty minutes of inactivity e.g I had to poo, I brought up the menu and went to take care of business , when I got back to the game the menu was still up, as soon as I exited the menu the game logged me out due to "inactivity" kind of annoying. column6: Xbox One 500GB Console - Assassin's Creed Unity Bundle
column13: but the PS4 is nothing like the PS3 in terms of media center hub
column14:
It's an Xbox One. I wanted a PS4, but the PS4 is nothing like the PS3 in terms of media center hub. Our Xbox360 was like a jet engine, so that didn't help either.

However, we have over 1,000 DLC songs for Rock Band (Xbox360), and they won't transfer to Sony's console, so that kind of made the decision pretty easy. We mostly use it for Netflix at the moment, if it even turns on at all (summer = rarely watch TV). It IS very quiet, so there's that, which is a huge plus for us.

Games... I don't know. I got GTA5 with it, but I hate FPS-style games on consoles because I grew up with mouse + keyboard. So I bought GTA5 for PC, and have played over 100 hours so far. I bought my wife Dragon Age: Inquisition, but she's a PC gamer as well, and has been addicted to Civ5 all summer (school teacher, this is her only time to play).

I'm sure there will eventually be non-FPS games (we love racing and sports and puzzle games) that will never come out for PC, so we'll eventually get our gaming in. Definitely when Rock Band 4 comes out this fall.

I'm still unhappy that I have to pay for XBL just to use Netflix and other apps. I don't play online on the consoles, only PC. But I paid just so I can cry and complain about it, though my normal brain assures me that eventually I'll use enough features to justify the $32 (got it on a great sale!). Plus, I am well aware of the fact that paying for a premium service means the service is generally superior to others. I own a PS3 as well, and Xbox has always been better in terms of online services, though Sony has definitely caught up these days. So I complain, but in the end, I understand and accept. It's a first-world problem. I guess I'm lucky enough to complain about paying $32 for a luxury when $32 in other parts of the world could buy life-saving medicine. Now I feel like a jerk for even owning an Xbox... what the...?

Pro:
quiet
fast
has all the proper apps like Netflix, Amazon Prime, Hulu, sports, etc
good games that I'll be interested in eventually
ROCK BAND 4! AND ALL OUR PREVIOUS DLC TRANSFERS!
somehow the controllers are even better than the 360's
built-in wireless and HDMI - I would have never bought another MS product if they made me go through the misery they did with the 360 and the separate and crummy wireless adapter and no HDMI port (yes, they added HDMI on the later ones... but I wasn't about to buy another 360 just for that).
Helped us decide to cancel DirecTV and save $113/month once we could get the NHL Center Ice package to work with XBL
MS always updates their consoles and adds excellent features (like backwards compat and DVR functions)

Cons:
sort of useless for the moment but that will slowly change over time
makes me sad that I waste energy complaining about having to buy Xbox Live Gold when other humans on the planet are living in horrible conditions
No HBO Now app yetmazon Prime, Hulu, sports, etc
good games that I'll be interested in eventually

column6: Lumines: Electronic Symphony - PlayStation Vita
column13: This is a really cool game that can be highly addictive
column14: This is a really cool game that can be highly addictive.  The playing mechanics are quite simple.  You get a block, each corner of the block is 1 of 2 colors.  You try to match the colors to the blocks that are already on the screen to create blocks that have all 4 sides the same color.  That's it.  There is a line that goes from left to right that matches the beat of the song that is playing, faster song means faster line.  The sound track has some great songs in it and this game can keep you going for quite some time.  The only reason I took off a star was the fact that the songs always play in the same order, I would have liked a shuffling of the songs so each play through would be different.

column6: EA SPORTS PGA TOUR
column13: Minimum Viable Product... And Not Much More
column14: Good news... It's the best golf game on Xbox One  Bad news... It's the only golf game on Xbox One*  The career mode leaves plenty to be desired. After three seasons of gameplay, it's pretty tired. And the character customization is pretty brutal if I'm being honest. Yes it's nice that I can use different grips and shafts for each club, but no I don't want to have to select it for my driver, woods, hybrids, irons and wedges independently.  Only thing left to do is play online mode. It gets a 3-star rating, but that's only because there's nothing else available on current gen consoles to compare it to. In contrast to the last Tiger Woods game, it leaves much to be desired.  *UPDATE 9/10/2015: As commenter "TS" points out, there is a current gen alternative to Rory McIlroy PGA Tour on Xbox One: "The Golf Club". However, it should be pointed out this alternative has no association with the PGA, R&A, golf courses like St. Andrews and Chambers Bay, brands like Taylor Made, Nike and Cobra and with no rights to use the likenesses of professional golfers like Rory McIlroy, Jordan Speith and Rickie Fowler. But apparently "it's a better game online, and it has developer's [sic] that actually care about the game, their customers, and who are continually coming out with updates to support the game and make it better." I apologize for any confusion my tongue-in-cheek review may have caused.

column6: UFC Undisputed 3
column14:
First off, dont buy this on Amazon for $60+. Go to Gamestop and buy it cheaper. Second, I'll keep this as short and sweet as humanly possible.

I'm no UFC fan. Never have been, never seen a single fight. My forte is COD, Battlefield, RPG, etc. First time in this realm of gaming outside of classic Mortal Combat and Street Fighter. That being said, this game you need.

Gameplay is superb. Combos are perfectly laid out and executed to perfection if landed. One can truly read the other fighter when skill permits. Also, skill levels are masterfully balanced.

As for the story. This is a UFC game. The story is you're starting off at the bottom and working your way through lower division into the upper echelon. In which, you "create a fighter " and progress him through.

Now, to the graphics. They are what you would expect for the 360. In addition, the slow motion camera will deliver pretty good knockout, jaw-rocking blows. It's nothing fancy but nothing short of what one would expect.

To conclude, this is one of my new favorites. Going from almost exclusively playing online shooters, this game has forever changed my outlook on fighting games. It's constantly engaging. If your dominating your weight class, many opportunities arise to challenge the class above or below. Honestly, this game never gets old and from constant play, I understand why Amazon os trying to get you for $60+.

But go buy this game used for $39 at Gamestop!

P.S. Taco Bueno is better than Bell ;)

column6: Splatoon
column13: Pretty additive game and surprisingly decent
column14: Surprisingly, in a year of overhyped games, this game is actually pretty addictive.  This is a game where the fun factor is the main focus of game, and it's really enjoyable for it.  The multiplayer mode can be quite a blast, and there are even Splatfests every now and then, where you pick from something like "Marshmallow vs Hotdogs" and fight against those who choose differently.  (Isn't fighting against those with different opinions fun?)  This is also one of those rare games, though a good amount of Nintendo games do have this feature, with a local multiplayer mode in it.  Of course, most in the age of online connectivity won't care that much about it, but for those who prefer local multiplayer or can't go online, this is a welcoming feature.  I just wish the servers are a bit better, as I remembered being able to play online on a weaker network than what I have right now.  This game also has a singleplayer mode, which is pretty light on the story and can be summed up in less than 5 minutes, but the levels are pretty fun, and I don't think the boss fights are that bad.  Your character is also customizable, though don't expect to go into a store in-game and just buy something for your Squid Kid.  You do have to play a few games online, up to level 4 to buy something from all stores, which isn't a big deal if you're able to play online.  Otherwise, this game is pretty much an addictive one, and it surpassed my expectations, which hasn't happened that much as of late.

column6: HUHD? HW-399M 2.4Ghz Optical Wireless Gaming Headset for XBox 360,Xbox one, PS4,PS3, PC, With Detachable Microphone
column13: Looking for a good budget PS4/PC headset? Look no further.
column14:
Ok So I will break this review down into the categories I find most important. I will upload pictures as soon as possible.

Construction/Build- So this headset is obviously a budget headset. At the price I paid (17.99 like new from Amazon Warehouse) it would be hard to complain unless this product was made extremely poorly. Well it's not. Although, being that I use A50's as my dailys, the comfort difference is substantial. These will not be the most comfortable headset you've ever felt, but it counters this by embracing it's cheaper materials. What I mean is that the padding is firm, but not too firm. This prevents the pressing of your ears causing them to ache after time. The earcups have no individual flex, which is probably my biggest complaint. So if you have a bigger head, the bottom of the headset (where the cord is attached) will stick out off your head. But as said before, the padding counteracts this by making sure no pressure is placed on the ears, which is key. The headband is perfect and gave me no discomfort after about 2-3 hours of gaming. Both are made with very breathable fabric rather than leather, which prevents sweat buildup. 4.5/5 for this category.

Aesthetics/Appearance - This is where this headset shines. I stream daily, and like headphones that are bold or cool to look at, and this headset nails it. I promise this headset looks just as good in person as it does in the images. The contrast of glossy/matte black with the blue padding is a real attention grabber, and frankly looks awesome. The mic (when attached) looks similar to a snake, and is much more appealing than a cord with a foam boom on the end. I wish more headsets took this bold approach rather than the boring dark colors. And to make this even better, the mic is detachable, which makes this perfect for wearing anywhere being that it only uses a 3.5mm jack. I've used this working out or just around the house doing chores, and looked awesome doing both :P 5/5

Sound Quality/Functinality - Oooook the big topic, how does it sound? I am no audiophile, but I'd like to say that I have a pretty good ear for good sound. This headset will not dissapoint in any way. Bass is not overly focused on and is clear and tight. This is my preferance being that most gaming headsets concentrate too hard on just bass, making it sound very muddy and distorted. Trust me when i say these sound good. Hip Hop/dubstep/electronic music played through these has very punchy bass, which is exactly how it should be. Mids and highs are equally balanced, and not overpowerd by the lows, leading to a great equalized experience. They get much louder than they need to (which is a plus for some) and plug directly into your controller for a ps4. Now for the mic. The mic is decent, as in you will sound fairly clear and should get no complaints from your friends. It does not compete with higher end headsets with quality mics though. But it also sounds better than the super cheap mics that drive everyone crazy when it sounds though your talking through a windstorm. 5/5

Summary - Fn Awesome headset for the price! Looks awesome, sounds great, feels nice. for under $25, it's only real competitor is the Sony Silvers, which it blows out of the water. If your on the fence, do it! You won't regret it!/>

column6: Assassin's Creed Rogue
column13: Good for the completionist; bad for the main story crowd.
column14:
This was a great addition to the Assassin's Creed franchise. It included the best of many aspects of past games, including: real estate improvement, passive income you collect from the bank, ships, a big city world (New York City) and TWO large ocean worlds (River Valley and Northern Atlantic), fishing/harpooning, hunting, and the assassin hunters that used the compass and whispers from the multiplayer games of Brotherhood through ACIII. Vast acres of wilderness were like ACIII, vast oceans like ACIV, plus ship wrecks to explore, assassin contracts to intercept and defend, and a unique story told from the perspective of the enemy, all contributed to this game being particularly fun.

The main storyline was short-ish, but not terribly so. I do think they could have made it about twice as long in order to utilize more locations. However, if you are a completionist, and enjoy wandering the world fulfilling tasks and collecting animus shards, this game offers plenty to entertain you. If you just play the main story, then take it out, yeah, this may be a disappointment.

This really is the top tier controller design at this point....except for the battery life. For as much effort as they put into this controllers design, you would think they would have thought through things better when it came to the POS battery they included, and since it's not really removable, you are kind of stuck with what you get, which, given some of the other features of the gamepad such as the cool light, fairly well guarantees that you will get at best between 4 to 6 hours per charge. It really is an amazing controller, but seriously Sony....get your stuff together and remedy the battery situation.

column6: Batman Arkham Origins
column13: A great game for $20 There's loads of content
column14:
A great game for $20

There's loads of content. Fun combat with mix of stealth and beat em up action that makes you genuinely feel like Batman. A zany Batman origin story many will love (though evidently it annoys some Batman fanboys?). There's also some small puzzles to solve. The Arkham series is actually very similar gameplay-wise to the Zelda series (puzzles, exploration, gadgets, intricate combat with lite RPG elements).

The WiiU gamepad provides a map of all the collectables, objectives, and other things to see and do in Arkham City. This provides tremendous ease in surveying the landscape and finding fun and interesting things to do. It's invaluable to a game like this -- I honestly wouldn't want to play this game without the WiiU gamepad. Arkham City uses the gamepad more extensively, but I think many players will find Origins use of the WiiU gamepad less overwhelming.

Other reviews mentioning technical problems with this game are pretty far exaggerated. In over 40 hrs of gameplay, the game only crashed on me twice (though in precisely the same gameplay circumstance). I never had any of the game progress killing bugs other versions of the game seemed to have. The game does dip below 30 fps more often then it should - making the fast-paced combat system a tad unfair as you can miss some important visual cues to dodge, counter, and strike. Other than that, Gotham City is bigger and more detailed than in Arkham City.

There is some additional downloadable content missing other versions have, but from what I hear, you're not missing much. This game alone should keep you (and your kids) happy and occupied for a long while. By no means a perfect game, but one the best you can get on the WiiU for the price point.

Even though the new battery didn't fix the power switch problem (guess my Gameboy advance sp is finally starting to die on me, though it is over 10 years old) the new battery keeps a charge just fine so at least there's that + the little Phillips head screwdriver is a nice little bonus.

column6: Lost Dimension
column13: Psychological Tension Ramped up to Eleven
column14: Lost Dimension is very unique as far as S-RPGs go. Rather than flood the player with convoluted storylines and dozens of esoteric game mechanics, the creators have elected to go for psychological warfare and terror. This is present from the instant the save system takes effect. The game auto-saves after each battle, and before each judgment. There are ways to circumvent this limitation, such as online saves, but that defeats the purpose of this. Besides, I'm personally too lazy to utilise such tactics.  There are flaws that make the game tedious at times, but they're minor when the greater whole is considered. Personally, I would love preset party members that are commonly used. This would save time at pre-battle screens. Vision Quests could be streamlined to take up less time. Some battles can take excessive amounts of time, and their frequency increases later in the game. I am hopeful that these and other issues will be mitigated when updates and DLC are made available.  Combat is especially tedious, especially given how easy it is. Very few levels have your foes conveniently placed a turn or two away from your starting locations. Fortunately, Agito can teleport everyone adjacent to him (at later levels). This makes things much more streamlined, although carrying character levels over would mitigate the need for this. At present, only skill points are available over multiple playthroughs.  Players will be taught to empathise with their teammates, and the randomised traitors makes every playthrough unique. To add to the sense of urgency and consequence, the game automatically saves before each judgment, so be wary before making an irrevocable choice at the denouement of each floor.

column6: Etrian Odyssey 2 Untold: The Fafnir Knight - Nintendo 3DS
column13: So good! Here's some differences I've noticed from the DS version if it helps anyone
column14:
I've played EO2 for the DS and it was a great game. I heard about this one, which is basically a remake of Heroes of Laagard with a story mode tossed in. Seeing as Atlus games are rarer than hen's teeth I thought it was better to grab it now then in a year when this thing's $100 a pop. Was it the right decision? Was it worth buying essentially the same game twice? IS it the same game twice??

Let's see the differences I noticed right off the bat:

Firstly, all the enemies are now animated. They look GREAT. Also, if they're close to death they'll have different animations showing them looking seriously wounded and beaten up. And even a little sad. Great detail here.

You have the option of starting a new game in Story Mode or Classic Mode. Story Mode uses a team of 5 preset classes and has a more in-depth storyline and includes voice overs. Personally, I haven't tried Story Mode yet but I plan to once I finish the game on Classic. In Classic Mode, you can create and choose from a giant list of character classes and make the best or most unusual team you can think of to take on the huge dungeon. My main team is Protector / Beast / Ronin / War Mage / Survivalist, and it's a bit unorthodox to say the least. But see that's one of this game's best selling points to me- Build your party any way you see fit, convention be damned!

There's three difficulty settings that you can change at any time. PICNIC is super easy from what I hear. I hear on the picnic setting the FOEs jump in the lake and drown themselves. (No, not really, but it's way too easy for most EO vets). Next is NORMAL which is tougher but not as tough as regular EO. I'm playing on EXPERT, which is something I'd never ever do, but it's supposed to be the most like "normal EO difficulty" so that's what I chose for now to start with.

Just like your main team, enemy formations can now also have a front and rear line. I think this is such an awesome addition, as it adds a lot of strategy and depth to the battles. This also means that a melee character (or enemy) in the back row can't attack the opposing back row.

NPC portraits now blink. THEY BLINK. This is sorta' creepy in practice. I'd rather they had taken the extra code space and added more possible character portraits but oh well. At least it's nowhere near as creepy as that Pink food merchant in NES' Faxanadu. (Google at your own risk!!)

The Survivalist character is actually pretty good now. I don't remember him being much more than the guy who mines for things and had crappy damage in the DS version, but here he has some decent bow skills almost right away (The Flank skill can attack an entire row of enemies for low TP, for example).

When you clear a floor, you'll have the option to Floor Jump. This means that you can be anywhere on the cleared floor later and can instantly return to the floor's staircase at the touch of the stylus. This is hugely important when you're surrounded by FOEs about to kick you keisters, or maybe if you get a sudden case of Lazy-itis-majorus.

There are Grimoires now (I've never played an EO game with these, but I guess they're in other installments too) that sort of act like Diablo's runes and can be attached to characters to give them different skills and etc (even enemy skills!) Further customization? Count me in!

Early on a restaurant will open up in the town. Here you can bring the ingredients you've found in the dungeon and add new dishes to their menu. Just like the food in Etrian Mystery Dungeon, eating here will grant your party different beneficial effects for a short while. It should be noted though that these dishes are not free later, as you'll have to purchase them for en (game money) to gain their effects. NOTE: Except for the very first time you figure a dish out- you'll get the effect for free then. You will also be able to name your restaruant, and yes "TACOBELL" will fit. Go ahead and do it, I did. Nobody will ever know.

Skills and Skill Trees are super improved in every way over the DS version. Before for example you'd have to spend a skill point on "Sword Mastery" which would raise your attack power with swords and eventually allow you to select other skills using a sword if you wanted to. Now, simply by raising your masteries those other related skills will be automatically learned for the cost of a single skill point (!!) This is great because it'll give players a chance to test out every basic skill and see if you like it without wasting points pumping into a skill that you'll never use later. The skill trees are also laid out much better than before. Extremely well done in this department.

Another thing I noticed is that there's no way for me to view how many times I can TAKE / CHOP / or MINE anymore. It used to be right on the main menu along with the STATUS / CUSTOM / PARTY / etc. options but they removed it for whatever reason. Sure would be good to know this offhand!

Day one DLC...... Well folks, it looks like there's just no way around it but almost every game company now is going to have this terrible model. If there's anything that Atlus does that's better though, is that most of the DLC options are free for a limited time. This includes the Highlander character class, original EO1 character portrait options, and some sidequests for example. Apparently, they're releasing more DLC all through this August 2015. I would recommend downloading the freebies at least, and maybe the ones that cost a couple bucks later on if you really think you can't live without it.per improved in every way over the DS version. column6: Lightning Returns: Final Fantasy XIII
column13: Great Battle System, Poor Game Design
column14: I'm torn about this game. I love the battle system. It's so much fun. I hate the daily clock, the eradia, and the fact that the game works against you. The player starts off at a disadvantage from day one because you need to use eradia to extend your time until the end of the world from six days to thirteen. To earn eradia, you have to complete side quests. The main quests earn you next to nothing in eradia. The game wants quantity, not quality, so you have to complete as many side quests in a day as possible. Even though I was running around like a crazy person and spending all of my TP to stop time (in order to give myself more time to complete quests), I still failed this game as I could not earn enough eradia to extend the time to thirteen days. Oh, and the leveling system is awful. You earn upgrades by completing side quests and quests from the Canvas of Prayers (which do not give you eradia). Without completing Canvas of Prayers quests, you have no chance of defeating many of the bosses in this game. I realize the game is designed so that players fail and have to play over and over again, but for me this is annoying. I like to power through games because I have little free time to play over and over.

column6: Retro Link GameCube Style USB Wired Controller
column13: Solid construction, but L and R triggers fall flat of their purpose
column14:
I wanted to love this controller when I unboxed it, as it felt like my original GameCube controllers in pretty much every way. Except, unfortunately, the one that mattered.

I purchased this controller so I could use the L and R trigger buttons with GameCube emulators such as Dolphin, but sadly the controller triggers just don't seem to have the firmware to support proper analog use where a light pressure has one result and pressing the trigger fully down gives the second result, a requirement in many, many, many GameCube games. Since this defeats the purpose for which I got the controller I had to return it. It's a perfectly serviceable controller, but not for what it's supposed to do, being a GameCube replica controller and all.

If you want to be able to use proper triggers in games like Super Mario Sunshine, do yourself a favor and get a real GameCube controller from Nintendo and a USB adapter like the MayFlash one instead.

column6: Hyrule Warriors
column13: That Zelda game you're supposed to hate, but can't
column14:
Hyrule Warriors is the Zelda game you're supposed to hate, but can't.

The story is a joke compared to the storytelling mastery of other Zelda games. But it's so off the wall, you can't help but want to dig deeper into it -especially as you can play as different characters good and evil from the story.

There are no intricate dungeons with clever puzzles - just a big battlefield where you more or less just go out and kill everything. But there's this remarkable feeling of progress and success as you capture more and more of the battefield. The satisfaction of conquering the battefield always stays fresh.

For the most part, you could button mash one button, use one weapon most of the game and beat it. Evidently that's what the Dynasty Warriors games are infamous for. But Hyrule Warriors rewards you taking out your enemies with some variety. As you master new combos and gain new items and pickup powerups on the battlefield, you learn new ways to kill more enemies faster. It's really awesome to see "1000 KO" pop-up on your screen after landing a string of magic attacks, power-up attacks, and other combos. "Rush Battle" - a scenario where you have 6 minutes to kill as many enemies as possible, really highlights this as what makes Hyrule Warriors so much to play.

It's a really fun new take on Zelda games, one that takes the series in some bold directions that I think Zelda fans young and old will appreciate.

column6: Call of Juarez: Bound in Blood
column13: I had heard good things about the game and it looked good when ...
column14:
Well, I had heard good things about the game and it looked good when I first put it in.

The controls are cow manure, the story is really bad, the two man voice actors are okay and every other voice actor is just gross (as in racist imitations of ethnic groups gross, which I can sometime handle this being a period game and all, but these were tastless), the animation is borish and worse than amateurish (I am used to seeing overly sexualized women in videogames but the way they animated the female lead was like giving a horny 16 year old with the coordination of a toddler the role of lead animator for this character) it was not only painful but embarrassing to watch, the horseback riding mechanics were really poor, and although some people are okay with the duel mechanics I had 4 differnet people play the game each one taking a minimum of 30 mintues to win a duel and none of us understood exactly how it worked even after reading tutorial after tutorial online almost nothing in the game was intuitive.

The things that were good include: the environments were really nicely done, the normal gameplay/ combat mechanics i.e. walk, run and shoot, the way the games equivalent to Rockstar's "Dead Eye" mode worked alrigh too.

I don't think I could ever play that game again. I think the moral of the story here is that Eastern Europeans should not make a game about the American Southwest or Civil War, especially if all they are going off is old photos and a few cowboy movies.

As an American, an animator, avid classic film lover and gamer this game just isn't worth the frustration or disgust.

column6: Final Fantasy XIII-2
column14: Ignoring the fact that Serah is the most annoying main character, the battle system for this game is awesome. I love the paradigm system, and I especially like the improvements they made in this game: it's no longer game over if your party leader is K.O.'d! There's a ton of fun add-on content for this game as well (which is totally optional to purchase and not necessary for beating the game, but fun to play none the less). Don't waste your money on the garb. It does nothing for the characters or game play. I also love that you can capture, train, and enhance monsters in this one. It takes me back to the days of Monster Rancher. I think if you like the Pokemon franchise, you'll probably be into this feature as well. The only thing I would say is that some of the alternate ending bosses are made way too tough. I'm currently stuck on battling Caius with just Serah and the monsters. Even maxed out, her HP is not high enough to survive his barrage of attacks. I'm going to have to figure out an alternative strategy. Aside from that, it's a fun game.

column6: PDP AG7 True Wireless Headset for Xbox One
column14:
The True Wireless HEADPHONES for Xbox One are just that. No wires, no cabling, no tethering to your controller. Simply stick the receiver into one of the Xbox One's USB ports, press the button on the left side to power up the headphones and you should be up and running. That simple.

Two dials on the back of the left earcup control game/console volume (top) and gamechat (lower). The boom mike is retactable and fully positional with LED indicating regular or bass modes.

The headphones are quite attractive and neither look nor feel like a novelty. The green LED afterglow lights are actually pretty cool but can be turned off if desired. They supposedly last 16 hours per charge via a USB cord, and after about eight hours I've had no drop off yet.

The headphones are a tad stiff but easily adjustable and the cups are comfortable as well as the headpiece cushion. I've only found myself taking them of to adjust for additional comfort and only after a few hours.

The sound is great and the fact that you can hear yourself through the Mic unlike other noise canceling headphones is a great feature. The chat volume is easy to find balance for, and the game sound is top notch beating out my Polks.

At $99 these have quickly become my go-to headphones and I plan to use them for a good long time.

column13: The Bokumono we've all been waiting for...
column14:
What can you even say about this game... the Bokumono update we've been waiting for. I'm VERY thrilled with the translation and localization work that XSeed provided for this game- after playing RF4, and comparing it to more recent Natsume localizations, I'm even more pleased that Marvelous is handing the reins over. Not since Harvest Moon 64 have I been so invested in a set of characters. Sure, the game does drag at times, but the interactions between your character and others, and even the NPCs, keep it lively. There's a bug in year 2 which makes your game crash... it's only happened to me once but that's a thing to be wary about. Street pass is.... interesting. My town is clogged with people. Not sure what they'll do but...

Seriously. If you've been waiting to play a good farming game again, this is the Harvest Moon that we've been needing- no longer Harvest Moon due to copyright shenanigans, but it's the Bokumono we all grew up with and loved, and better than ever. Highly recommend.

The main things that are disappointing are that the create-a-move and custom soundtrack for entrances are gone, along with a lot of the generic/past superstar entrances that could be used for your create-a-wrestlers. I'm pretty bummed by that, since I used a lot of those for my create-a-wrestlers.
For a good thing, the basic game play is still there and they didn't remove any create-a-wrestler parts. You can also have up to 100 create-a-wrestlers on the 360, which is pretty sweet. There are also a handful of the newer wrestlers and NXT guys, so that's kinda cool.
The 2k Showcase and Who Got Next modes are kinda interesting, but do feel a bit tedious sometimes. This is especially true in the Who Got NXT mode. The objectives in the Showcases actually pertain to parts of the story line, but trying to hit all the objectives in Who Got NXT can get frustrating and tedious, especially on higher difficulties.
That being said, the HHH/Shawn Michaels showcase was a pleasant trip down memory lane and the CM Punk/John Cena story in the other is probably the best story line the WWE had in years.As for the DLC showcase, I haven't downloaded/played it, but honestly, who wants to re-live the painfully one-sided Christian/Orton rivalry?
To sum it up, this game isn't terrible, but it's not the best WWE game out there, either. Hopefully, 2K16 will bring back more of the custom entrances and the ability to have a custom soundtrack for an entrance.

column6: Deus Ex
column14:
Deus Ex is arguably the greatest PC game of all time. It appears frequently at or near the top of best ever lists by both journalists and the gaming public alike. It was ranked #1 of the top 100 PC games of all time by PC Gamer, PC gaming's most widely respected publication.

These accolades are no surprise when one sees how brilliantly the game succeeds on so many levels. The story is a masterfully crafted, globe-hopping cyberpunk adventure through which the player's character navigates a dystopian future world on a mission to unravel a Gordian Knot of conspiracies, secrets and lies. Both the player's character and the world he inhabits are shaped by nanotechnology, the former for better, the latter for worse. The player assumes the role of JC Denton, an agent of UNATCO, an international anti-terrorism organization. The terror he combats is largely attributable to the Gray Death, a nanomechanical virus that has ravaged the planet. Denton, however, is immune to the virus thanks to nano-augmentation, a cutting-edge technology available only to elite government agents. Nano-augmentation endows Denton with an array of superhuman powers such as infrared vision and invisibility. Augmentations may be customized to suit a particular playing style, for example stealth artists may opt for the footstep-silencing lower body augmentation while aggressive circle-strafing gunners can choose increased speed. The game's augmentations perfectly complement the open-ended design that is its greatest feature of all. Every level features secret areas for circumventing enemies, gathering intel or finding resources. These avenues might be accessible only with certain abilities, for example a fence might be surmountable only to players with the speed-boosting aug that allows them to leap it or the strength-boosting aug that allows them to stack enough heavy crates to climb it. Every mission can be approached in multiple ways using stealth, force, diplomacy or a combination of the three. The story itself actually adapts to the ramifications of the player's approach to the missions. The game is so open-ended, in fact, that there are only two required neutralizations. It can played as a straight-up run-and-gun shooter, a sneak-through-the-shadows stealth adventure or anywhere in between. Further complementing the open-ended gameplay is the RPG-style stat system in which players can develop proficiency in certain weapons or skills such as hacking, lockpicking, or even swimming. This level of freedom was unprecedented in shooters at the time of the game's release. Before, such games would tell the player "Go here, do this." Deus Ex, through the very end, asks: "What do you want to do?"

Deus Ex is superb in other aspects as well: There is a great arsenal of weapons both lethal and non-lethal, familiar and futuristic. A favorite of many is the nano-edged sword, which when combined with footstep silencing aug, is immensely fun to assassinate enemies with. The weaponry is so well-integrated with the augmentation and skill systems that by the end of the game the player feels like a techno-deity. Although the story veers rather outlandish at times, the game never stops encouraging players to think skeptically. The graphics, from an artistic standpoint, convey the game world's bleakness very effectively. The game is set entirely during dusk and nighttime; blues, blacks and grays feature predominantly in its palette. The soundtrack never feels incongruous with its setting and the theme music is one of the most memorable in gaming history.

Deus Ex is not a technically perfect game. Its graphics were somewhat dated at the time of release, the foreign accents are hilariously bad and the boss fights are a drag (though all but two are optional). These flaws do not detract, however, from what a monumental achievement this game is. Deus Ex may not be the most technically polished game of all time, but it is among the mostinfluential. Doom and Wolfenstein 3D established the first-person shooter as a genre, but Deus Ex elevated it to an art form. This was accomplished through its ingenious fusion of role-playing elements with familiar shooter conventions, giving birth to a new genre: the action RPG. The action-RPG has become one of today's most popular genres; echoes of Deus Ex can be seen everywhere, from the decision-trees of the Mass Effect trilogy to the plasmids of BioShock.

Any game as influential as Deus Ex must be considered a classic, but to call this game a classic is almost an understatement. The defining aspect of video games as a medium is interactivity, and interactivity is maximized when players are granted as much freedom to shape their role within a game as possible. Deus Ex fostered this freedom to the utmost degree. Deus Ex was not only the instantiation of a new genre, it was and remains to this day, the highest instantiation of what a game can be.tein 3D established the first-person shooter as a genre, but Deus Ex elevated it to an art form. column6: Trials Fusion
column13: Very Addicting, Lots of Fun for all ages
column14:
This game is hours of fun for all ages, I am in my late 20's and love this game. I played a demo of this game in a store and I was hooked, I went home and ordered it. This game has limitless content, the ability to build your own tracks, great training levels and the ability to play multiplayer. The game does have its frustrating moments as some levels are very difficult but if you are a competitive person you will love the challenge. The visuals are also very clear which adds to the fun, the camera angles make it feel as if you are really on the bike and the learning tutorials are actually a lot of fun unlike some games where the tutorials are boring. The game also has humorous comments and sound effects that I enjoy.

I can't really think of any cons in this game except for some of the levels that are very difficult but if you keep at it, you will eventually learn all the tricks to get through the rough patches but it does take some time and patience to learn thing such as doing backflips without crashing. Once you master it though its very fun.

column13: One of the best farming simulators.
column14: This a great Harvest Moon game. I'm not much for DS games but I got pretty hooked on this. There were probably more options in this game then I have ever seen in any of the series. While this is a bit overwhelming for a while, having all these new responsibilities was fun and kept me playing. It's similar to most Harvest Moon games; managing a farm/ranch, making friends with villagers, potentially marrying one of the bachelors/bachlorettes and starting a family, fixing up your place and the town, and also participating in town events and contests. The game includes a few new mechanics including, making your own clothing from scratch, swimming, new livestock and crops, and the new trade depot. There are also new sheds to build for making new items including the pottery barn, sewing studio, and winery. This is a truly fun Harvest Moon game and there is LOADS to do. This game could possibly be too much for a younger player as it can be a bit confusing and make you feel like your just drowning in things to do but it's still a really great installment and a lot of fun to play around with once you get the hang of it.

column6: Diablo III: Ultimate Evil Edition
column13: Sweet Game, many hours of entertainment.
column14: I've been playing this game for a few weeks and I really like it.  I played the demo on the PS Store, and my character from the demo transferred into the game.  It was nice starting at lvl 7 from the start.  This game reminds me a little bit of Gauntlet or Gauntlet Legends, in that it's a dungeon kind of a dungeon crawler with the classic overhead view.  The game is pretty deep as far as customization options go for your character.  I have already reached Act V and I feel like I'm just kind of scratching the surface of the weapons/jewels system.  I will definitely be playing this game again (probably several times) so that I can pick a different character class and see what that's all about.  Being new to the Diablo series, it didn't take me long to figure out the story lines, etc.  It's not the most in depth story, and I honestly don't give a crap about a lot of the characters back-stories, but man, the gameplay itself is addicting.  I am OCD and have to cover all of the map before I can move on and that has turned out to be pretty rewarding.  I haven't gotten in to the expansion stuff yet either, but so far so good.  I never have gotten my "Legendary Item" from battle.net though, and I followed all the instructions on the website etc. but with so many other items in the game I'm not that worried about it.  There are endless items in this game with 100's of different attributes and benefits.  I needed something to game on this summer while I save up for a PS4, and this is going to provide many hours of entertainment.  Well done, as usual, Blizzard.

column14:
If you enjoyed Batman: Arkham Asylum, Arkham City (and to a lesser extent Arkham Origins) then you have expectations for this game. And it does not disappoint. The Batmobile is added as a third leg to the game dynamic (the other two being brawling and stealth) and it functions well in both racing and tank combat modes. By the end of the game you will find yourself getting a little tired of the repetitive tank combat, but beating the bejeezus out of group of thugs with your bare hands while muttering "I'm Batman" will break up the tedium.
Why 4 stars? Well, the tank combat gets boring, there's another huge glut of Riddler fetch quests, and pathing bugs on armed goons (oddly only happening to me during Origins but not the other two) during the predator sections all detract from the game. End of the day though you get to glide through the air, dive tackle a goon, and proceed to beat the tar out his friends until they run away in terror. All in a days work for the Batman.
