column6: Nyko Data Bank
column13: Avoid at all costs! Does not work and could damage your PS4.
column14:
Went through multiple installation attempts, each time the update was installed via USB and the PS4 would restart and the system would crash. Tried several WD Greens, 2TB, 3TB, and a 4TB WD Red. Tried formatting to eX as recommended. Tested drives in a PC and they work just fine. Took everything apart and re-seated everything to the same results. I swore I would never buy another product from Nyko after their inter-cooler burned out the video board on my Wii, and now I know I never will.

Even just in the install loop that I was getting stuck in, the unit runs EXTREMELY HOT. The ps4 is clearly not made to be having this additional power being drained. Even if the product works for you as advertised, I'm willing to bet it will shorten the life of the console. Heed my words, stay away from this terrible product.

column6: Lost Dimension
column14:
I normally don't review video games but this one I will make the exception.
I heard about this game from a friend and Anime Expo. I was very intrigued by the whodunit mechanics and decided to buy it without any other reviews or ratings to go by. Now I'm not very far but I can say right now I am throughly enjoying this game. It is slow paced and even a little repetitious at times but I cant stop playing it!
I'm hooked on knowing more about the story even if it is very simple and I love all the characters and have grown very attached to them. Killing off the traitor has been very emotional for me.
My only problem with this game is that I don't see much replay ability. Aside from different traitors that look like the only thing that does change.
I did get a ton of free DLC. Costumes and exrta missions which add to the story. Not sure of they will be free for long but I'm happy Atlus offered them. Some reviews said that game was too easy. I am having a little difficulty with it myself. My party members get ganged up on then die and reviving them is pointless becuse they will get ganged up on again and die. And even if leveling and suiting up your characters are a little simplified compared to most RPG's this game still has a nice bit of customization and it makes you want to level up your traitors so you can extract their best abilities for your own use.
I won't prattle too much longer. Just all in all I love this simlple game. It has engaged me while lately I'm having a hard time playing other games I have started. So if you want simple good anime rpg fun get this game! Im certainly enjoying it.

column6: Persona 4 Golden - PlayStation Vita
column14:
The rumors and reputation that this game has is enormous. Does the game live up to the hype?

You bet it does!

This is a must have for any ps vita owner. I never played a persona game before, but this game made me a fan.

What's great about this game? Well, first of all, from the opening video, you can tell thus game was perfect for the vita. The vibrant colors of the game are reflected on the PS vita's amazing iled screen. Not to mention the unforgettable soundtrack. I love every song in the game and the main composer of the game, Shoji meguro, has a unique style to his music.

Gameplay involves solving a murder mystery by dungeon grinding while living out your school life in between battles. The best part of the game has to be the character interactions you have as you progress through the game. You will love every single one of them, and none of them are as simple as you think! The vita version of the game also adds a new character for you to know. Although I wasn't a big fan of the character, it was still a nice addition to the game.

Overall, persona 4 golden is the pinnacle of a jrpg. It's got the story, the music, the gameplay, and the characters. If you dont have the game yet, go get it now. It's just that good.

column6: Zettaguard Wireless PC USB Gaming Receiver for Xbox 360 Compact Disc
column13: I BOUGHT THIS FROM OCEAN BEST OR SOMETHING CLOSE
column14:
NOTE: I BOUGHT THIS FROM OCEAN BEST OR SOMETHING CLOSE, AND THE REVIEW APPLIES TO THEM
The product it came with was a cheap Chinese knock-off of the official Microsoft version, and it was obvious. It came with a disk for the drivers and manual. However, the drivers it came with were fake or broken. When you try to use the drivers it comes with, windows alerts you that it found the drivers, but they couldn't be installed because they were corrupted or broken. It even admits to being fake in the title of the drivers, as it says "Could not install drivers for 'Microsoft Xbox 360 Adapter Fake' because...". Now, this is fixable if you buy it. You can just ignore the drivers it came with, download the official ones of Microsoft's site (link to guide for fix: https://krisrowland.wordpress.com/2011/06/09/fake-microsoft-xbox-360-wireless-controller-adapter-in-windows-7-64-bit/). So, the product they give you is incomplete, but with thirty minutes of tinkering, it will work.

column6: Theatrhythm Final Fantasy: Curtain Call
column13: This Fantasy Lasts a Long Time...
column14:
This game is an amazing amount of fun, especially if you like Elite Beat Agents or Dance Dance Revolution. The music of Final Fantasy is given a chance to shine here, and most of it is extremely enjoyable.

Gameplay: I am most comfortable on the Basic difficulty level. I got some exposure to harder difficulty in the Quest Medley mode. That helped me to refine my timing, but the overall experience on the harder difficulties is much more stressful. Basic is the best way to just enjoy the music and tap and slide along to it at a comfortable pace.

There are so many characters, items, and RPG elements included in the game, but I am not sure what most of them do. There is so much to do just in playing all the songs and modes that I have not hit bottom yet of all the options. It is fun to unlock the trophies in this game. Some will just happen naturally, while others you can figure out from the hints on the trophy records page.

This game is a love letter to Final Fantasy and its music, and it is one of the 20 best 3DS games.

column6: Xbox Live Subscription
column13: Cheapest and most Secure way to pay for Xbox Live
column14:
The first decision you have to make is whether or not a Gold Subscription to XBox Live is worth it. If you want to stream movies from Netflix or HBO it's not really an option. If you want to game online pay up!

Once you've decided to subscribe the cheapest and safest way to pay for your subscription is through a gift card / online game code. Amazon seems to always have a lower price than Microsoft (or any other retailer) and you only share your credit card information with Amazon. If Xbox Live ever get's hacked like Sony did you'll have one less thing to worry about.

The redemption process is simple, sign into xbox.com and redeem the code!

Simple as that: cheaper and more secure!

column6: StarCraft II
column13: A review on the single-player experience
column14:
I just got started about a year ago, so this review will strictly concern itself with the campaigns, as I never played WoL multiplayer and have no basis to compare the experience of the original versus the expansion.

To preface further, I grew up playing Blizzard games and have always felt immersed by both the gameplay, and the plot/atmosphere/music.

The WoL campaign was awfully fun, did a great job of introducing the new mechanics and all the units, and I thoroughly enjoyed the plot and all the characters, even if it wasn't quite as dark and creepy as I remember the original SC campaign to be.

With HoTS, as others have noted, the dialogue isn't well written, there aren't any characters to really connect with, the campaign feels shorter on account of the missions not being as epic and varied as in WoL, and it was really too easy with the Kerrigan hero unit. I remember really struggling with some of the WoL on hard, particularly the last mission "All In" which took me about twelve tries. On hard, I beat the final HoTS mission on the third try, and I don't even remember its name which goes to show how memorable it was.

They did some really interesting things with the HoTS campaign, and there were some really fun missions, but playing through it, it really feels as if only 50% of the effort and care that was put into the WoL campaign was put into HoTS. I could have even put up with the downgrade in mission quality/variety if there had been a solid plot, or vice versa, but the single-player experience with HoTS really feels rushed, incomplete, almost as if it were an afterthought, something "compulsory" that had to come with the expansion with the focus being on changes to the multiplayer mechanics.

Taken on its own, the campaign is fun or I wouldn't have even played through it. It's just so underwhelming compared to WoL.

column6: U.S Army Elite Force Assault Rifle Controller For PlayStation 3 & Move
column13: Near Perfect VR Gun Controller--Coming from Sharpshooter
column14: Was looking for a replacement of my PS Sharpshooter for my future VR setup and this is a huge upgrade. For now, I'm only testing this gun on PC so I can't speak to using it with PS3 games and how well it performs.  Pros: - Appearance: Not to be shallow but this gun just looks awesome-it's modeled after the m4a1 rifle used by the military. Camo is cool but some might prefer black. -Easy-setup: Just plugged the USB dongle in PC and, using controller mapping software, the gun was up and running. -Move compatibility: Could be used on my PS3 with Move if I desired. -Fore-grip and stock: First time I've seen a fore-grip on a peripheral gun and it does ease prolonged handling when compared to the Sharpshooter and how its significantly more front heavy. -Buttons: Has all the buttons on a PS3 controller and an additional thumb-stick compared to the Sharpshooter. -Lightweight: Weighted both guns and the Force Elite is much lighter than the Sharpshooter (fully loaded). -Rumble: Gun mimics rumble of PS3 controller (albeit, kinda weak). -Handling: It's comfortable to hold and handle. -Army licensed: Can't remember Army ever doing this but it's cool that their involved. -Scope: Not at all useful for my VR setup but cool looking nonetheless.  Cons: -Thumbstick: It's smooth compared to the rough surface of its controller counterpart. -Button placement: Alot has been commented about this but my hands adapted pretty fast to tight placement of the buttons. The only other issue is the thumbstick on the handle and how my thumb would constantly bump on the area right above the thumbstick. -Trigger: There's a little too much friction when pulling; Sharpshooter is smoother by comparison. -Price: at over $50, it's more expense than most of its competitors but, in my opinion, all of its features justify the price premium. -Iron Sight: This is Nitpicky, but CTA should have chosen the classic M4 ironsight (surprise Army didn't insist); it's removable so it's not a big problem.  I was seriouslyconsidering this or the Top Shot Elite and I couldn't be more happy with my choice. It looks and handles wonderfully and I would recommend it to others who are in the same VR preparation as I am.

column6: Turtle Beach - Ear Force Recon 30X Chat Communicator Gaming Headset - Xbox One (compatible w/ new Xbox One controller), PS4, PC, Mac, and Mobile
column14:
I don't have an Xbox one, but I do have a PS4. I also rarely play online multiplayer games, but when I do I have been frustrated at being the only one not able to communicate. These did the trick. When the arrived I panicked because they clearly look to be designed for the PS4. Also they looked pretty big and my head is fairly small. So when I finally had some free time I sat town and discovered that they do plug into the PS4 remote and the PS4 acknowledged that they were there. So I fiddled around with them but was confused at first because the sound kept coming out of my TV. It wasn't until I was in the multiplayer that I realized that only conversation with other players was coming over the headset. I could hear them okay and they said that they could hear me - so on that end it seemed to be working. Having the headset on was frightening to my dogs - who believed that I had become a Borg. I had to put it on and take it off several times before they went to their regular gaming snooze locations, finally convinced that I didn't require help. The fit was fine, and it wasn't uncomfortable to wear.

Final thoughts - if you are a casual gamer who just wants to talk to people occasionally while playing - this will work for you. If you treat gaming like it's your job - you may want to spent more money.

column6: Final Fantasy XIII
column14: Great characters, great story, exciting new battle system. The only downside that I can find is that if your party leader gets K.O.'d, it's game over. It can also be difficult because you can only directly control your party leader, so if you need to use a specific character's ability or summon, you need that character to be the party leader because there's no way to ensure that the computer will auto-cast those spells for you. Unfortunately, some of the characters with the most useful abilities are also physically the weakest. For example, Vanille is the only character that can cast Death, but she has thousands of HP less than other characters, so if you're battling a tough monster (e.g. Ochu), she will probably get K.O.'d a few times, forcing you to start the battle over. I did appreciate that effort was made on the part of the game designers to curb the amount of time needed to level up your characters. For the majority of the game, you don't need to go out of your way to grind levels. It will level up through normal game play. They also added side quests when the game does slow, forcing you to grind, so that rather than relying solely on random encounters, you can work toward goals which will actually help your characters acquire better weapons and accessories in the process. Overall, I found this game to be enjoyable. I'm finishing up the last of the missions now, then going back to battle the final bosses again.

column6: Bound by Flame
column13: Needs work but a decent time filler between blockbuster games
column14: I actually intended to buy Dragons Age Inquisition, but I saw this one on sale and thought I'd give it a try. It does have above decent graphics and the beginnings of a good storyline. The fighting style is very hard to control and takes some getting used to, but I got used to it after first hour. The character dialog throws you off a little as it is mismatched to their lips and looks like a Playstation 1 mouth speech engine lol. I got a little tired of the constant close quarters trails intertwining and confusing trails, broken up only by the open-air combat areas. I could always tell when I was fixing to run into some enemies because the terrain would go from narrow passages to a space where you could actually move around a little. I played this game for a little while until DAI came on sale, which I bought and am very satisfied with. I have not attempted to complete this game as I was only half-way compelled to play it. In my opinion, a good game should make you think about it while you're at work instead of a last resort on a Tuesday night.For $20, it had the makings of a good time filler in between great games. I recommend picking this game up on sale and enjoying it when you're between games. I'm personally saving this one for my son so I can say "look son, look at the speech dialog we used to have to put up with back in my day" haha

column6: Action Replay 4M Plus - Ultimate enhancement for your Saturn console
column14: These are known for bricking, which was painful for me to learn. I thought I had a problem with my Saturn so I almost opened up the console and risked damaging it rather than learning that the cart can be unreliable. I went to the Saturn forum to show everyone a picture of my console's cartridge slot to see if that was the problem, and everyone told me that it's the cart, as the slot looks fine.  A cart like this is a necessity for Saturn owners (especially in the US and PAL territories), but if a product doesn't work, then it's a bad product. I have moved past and purchased an Interact GameShark, which is working perfectly!   But also be weary of the GameShark: The board inside the cart is larger than an official memory card, so constant removing and inserting can damage the pins on the Saturn's cartridge slot. The trick is to put the GameShark in and leave it. NEVER take it out unless absolutely necessary.

column6: Hybrid Heaven
column13: Hybrid Heaven - One of the best from Konami
column14:
Take an alien conspiracy. Add in some cloning. Season with a bit of Total Recall, and then stir it all together with some wicked wrestling, and you get HYBRID HEAVEN!

This is one of those titles that requires the player to move past initial assumptions. Give it a go, and forge ahead through the strangeness, and I bet you'll get as hooked on the plot as I did. The combat mechanics essentially takes some of the best wrestling visuals (of the time) and ties it to a turn-based system. You can maneuver while your action bar fills up, and then unleash powerful suplexes and submissions to put a world of hurt on alien scum.

There is also a bit of third-person shooter, but basically you use a pop-gun to zap security drones, while avoiding devious traps and deciphering puzzling mazes. Just when you think you got it all figured out...

An excellent title. A MUST for N64 fans. Now if only they'd do a sequel...

column6: Rayman Legends
column14:
I will be splitting this review into to 2 parts 1. Content 2. Should you buy it / Final Thoughts

1. Content Rayman Legends is the successor to the game Rayman Origins which is also on the Vita. Rayman Legends is a 2D side scroller action game. If you played Mario games then you know what your getting your self into. You control Rayman and complete various levels every 2 to 3 levels you will have to control this character named Murpy while playing the Murpy stages you cannot control him you have to use the touch screen or touch pad on the vita to control him also using the Gyro senser from time to time. The graphics of the game are Amazing. I do own Killzone Mercenery and in my opinion I think this is about the best graphics you can get on the vita. if any game on vita was going to impress your friends in terms of consol graphics on the go this would do it. Now this game is packed with content you have the main game which the story is just average nothing to blow you away and then you can unlock new characters to play as I think around 20+ there really just skins they dont really play diffrent from each other you also got challenge mode plus the edition of Kickfoo which is a soccer type mini game. There is no game plus or extra world to unlock for 100% completion however the coolest thing that ubi did is bring back some of the best stages from Origins and put them in Legends as bonus stages around 30 or so levels from that game. To unlock them you have to use these shamrock type scratch tickets in the game. The game aslo has 2 player co- op but no one I no owns a vita sadly. The best levels they included in the game are these music type stages were you run and jump to the music in the background there very innovative. Over all for the price and as a platformer Legends is packed full of content from start to finish dont forget when you get the game to update it they added 25 invasion levels free there clock based speed running levels. The vita versionalso has 5 Murpy levels not seen on any other consol. The music in each level feels like it should be in a movie thats how good it is. None of the music gets stale its very good .

2. Should You buy/Final Thoughts - This is by far my favorite Vita game I would go all the way to say I would put this in my top 10 even top 3 vita games of all time. Now you may be asking your self why I gave it 4 out 5 star when I gave it so much praise. I really want to give this game 5 star but the thing that ruins the game for me not giving it a 5 star is those Murpy stages with full Touchscreen gameplay and Gyroscoop controlls tilting the system Who at Ubi soft thought those levels were a good idea Who???... I never liked gimmicky type stages but to be fair they do work well. Im not into touch screen cellphone type games that use only touch screen but thats just me you may actually like those stages. Its kinda like when the Nintendo DS came out for the first time and devs were trying to use the touch screen all the time just because it was there. I found my self having to hold the Vita in one hand when I play the Mupry stages which makes it hard to play the vita.I just really love the game Allot!!! But the murpy stages subtract 1 star. Also to mention the game only has 1 game save file so if you and your family or friends want to play the game they will have to delete your game save to start there own unless they have there on vita agian I dont know why they couldn't easily have 2 to 3 game save files which bugs me a little. Even though Murpy stages are there and no multiple game saves its not enough for me to give this game a very bad score when this game has allot of content and beautiful graphics on vita maybe the best bang for your buck on Vita. Overall I Would deff recommend this game to any vita owner its worth every penny of the admission price to play. Should you buy it on vita or another consol? I do love the game so... much I actually bought it on the Wii U as well but what I can say is there almost identical expect the vita has 5 new murpy stages and obviously you can take it with you wherever go. I would get it on vita without a doubt in my mind this may be my favorite 2d platformer this gen on a handheld. If you were wondering this game is not on 3ds they did give 3ds origins though. I really do like the fact that the origion stages are here to play they could of easily said welp origion stages will cost 10 to 15$ paid dlc to reply those stages but they didnt it seems like ubi this time around made the game for the consumer not just to make money. Thumbs up to Rayman Legends!!!

column6: EA SPORTS PGA TOUR
column13: Four! - Watch Out for A Poor Golf Game
column14:
Not sure where to start. This game is a mess. EA took last year off to rebuild their golf game. They should have taken at least one more. This game is just not fun and the putting is terrible.

To start with, this is as about bare bones as a golf game could be. Check out some of the more in-depth reviews if you want a full break down on what this game does (and does not) have. But just for examples sake, during create a mode, I was in and had my character created in about 45 seconds. This process in slimmed down create a character modes in other games still usually takes me a good 5 to 10 minutes. There was just nothing to do here. They would have been better off just giving you a generic character to play. The simplicity and lack of options just demonstrates how poor the game is.

The play styles are the only highlight of the game. They offer a classic 3-click mode, a pro mode that tracks your swing motion on the thumb stick, and a arcade mode that lets you flick away on the thumb stick with a generous margin for error. Just about any player with any skill level can pick the game up and play.

I had heard that the game was beautiful and there were no load times between holes. This isn't quite true. The game does not have any loading specific screens, but the leader board was shown in between each hole during my play through, and there was a delay in between when I could advance to the next hole. I have to imagine while these are not technically labeled load screens, there is some loading going on in the background. As far as being beautiful... well, not so much. Much of the color looked washed out. There was a hilarious amount of "popping" as elements suddenly appeared on screen that were not there before. During the opening intro cinematic, the camera pans across a field of grass and random flowers just start popping into the picture in the middle of the grass. All things considered, there is not the leap I would expect between the graphics on the last EA golf game and this, the first one on next gen hardware.

Unless you are desperate for a golf game on console, I would stay away. Or go pick up Mario Golf on the DS, at least the putting works there. Give EA another year to refine the game and flesh it out more. There are things that may be good about this game, they are just hard to focus or even recognize with so much missing from it. Maybe EA can flip that come next year's game.

column6: NVIDIA Shield Portable Starter Pack
column14:
I originally purchased the shield portable three or four years ago. At first i loved it, with Kodi, I could watch movies, Tv, listen to music, etc all from my magic little box- what's not to love? It runs emulators, and is also capable of casting or plugging into a television to use as a traditional console.

All of the things shield was advertised as, I assure you, are true.

HOWEVER, there are a number of COMMON mechanical issues that signal a death knell for your shield. The touch screen is guaranteed to fail eventually, as was the case with my unit. This renders many of the apps supported by the unit (including certain emulators) useless. Furthermore, replacements for the screen are unavailable and near impossible to install (if you are lucky or wealthy enough to find one). The mini HDMI port on my shield was broken before I received it, and unfortunately I did not attempt to use it until my console was at it's end of life.

While the shield, is a mechanical marvel, and a magnificent entertainment device while it lasts, I'm sorry to say that it's durability (in lieu of available replacement parts) is significantly lacking. These mechanical issues are common, please do your own research surfing the forums before purchasing a console.

column6: Hatsune Miku: Project Diva F 2nd
column14:
I am glad that after the success of Project diva F's debut in America that the sequel was localized as well. The game is rhythm game that involves Vocaloid songs if you didn't know, and this game improves all that the original project diva f had to offer. The resolution on the vita has been cleared up and the game no longer looks blurry. The song selection is also quite varied with additional songs available as dlc. Old data from the other game can be transfered over so you can still use the old costumes from the other game!

The only complaint I have is segas decision to divide the edit song (custom song) database. Apparently now the japanese edit songs are impossible to play now on the North America versions of the game due to the addition of more characters being available to write into songs to accommodate english words. That means we miss out on all the creative videos that other people have created around the world! I would have rather had them not make this change p I probably would have imported the game instead if I knew about it because edit songs can really make this game more interesting. It's still fun if you don't care about that though. The base game is still addicting.

Miku's return has been awesome and I highly recommend this as a rhythm game fan despite its lackluster edit songs.

column6: PlayStation All-Stars Battle Royale
column13: It's multiplayer-filled fun, for a time!
column14:
It has a thoughtful roster. (Sadly, it feels rushed.) The gameplay is fun, and I would say it feels different than "SSB's". I have played it for months. My favorite characters are Dante, Evil Cole, Jak, and Sly. I ended up mastering the first (3) with practice. The gameplay was made, to have players create their own combos. (I'm serious!) I would recommend this, instead of the suggested combos, from the character tutorials. Characters could roll, and block. Some of the roster has characters, that could parry, or Sly, who turns invisible, instead of blocking. There are also cheap grab moves! The game itself, focuses of one-shot KO's. All players need to build their "Super" meter, and use it for a cool KO move. Supers are separated into (3) levels. All are best for certain situations. Players must build "AP" by attacking their opponents, so they could use a super. I would go and say, all characters have CHEAP abilities. That's just how it is. It might be frustrating at times, but its a game that will be fun, if you practice. Learn even by watching your teammates, or opponents. The stages are from many other (PlayStation) games. I find it a bit strange. This is how a stage works. You're in one place and all of a sudden, there are hazards, and the backgrounds change. It's another game setting intersecting the one in place. One of my favorites, is "Alden's Tower" from inFAMOUS, which goes to Sly's rooftops. (Clearly, its a Sucker Punch reference.) It's a strange, but fun feature. (Hey, even Patapon made it...) All of the backgrounds are animated well.

There are 4 DLC characters, which are fine. I loved them, despite a couple feeling odd. If you of course purchase the PS3 version, you will get the digital VITA version for free! This is a great deal that can't be ignored, unless you don't own a PS3. One of the coolest features is the cross-play. PS3 and VITA players, could play matches with each other! So, grab your friends, and have some fun!

Replay value: There's an arcade mode with a story, and each character rivals another. You have tons of multiplayer hours here. (I actually felt bored from the arcade mode. It's too easy, and slow.) I don't recommend this game, unless you love these characters, but also expect to spend lots of time in multiplayer. (That's local, or online! Yes, bots are included!) Aside from the gameplay, there are a great set of trophies here.fun! Replay value: There's an arcade mode with a story, and each character rivals another. You have tons of multiplayer hours here.
